<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WMO Holds Meeting on El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Meteorological
Organization (WMO) held a first follow-up meeting on El Nino here
today after a United Nations inter-agency task force on the
phenomenon was set up on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will provide scientific and technical information
on the current status of El Nino, as one of the major forces
acting on the global climate system and with a potential to affect
weather patterns in many areas of the globe.
</P>
<P>
According to WMO, strong warm episode (El Nino) conditions have
persisted in the tropical Pacific since July 1997. Sea surface
temperatures throughout the equatorial east-central Pacific
increased during April and May, when temperatures normally
decrease in this region.
</P>
<P>
During August and September, ocean surface temperatures reached
near-record levels in many sections of the equatorial Pacific.
Departures from normal exceeded +4 degrees Celsius along the
Equator east of 120 degrees West, and were greater than +5 degrees
Celsius near the Galapagos Islands and along the coast of northern
Peru, WMO says in its new publication, El Nino Update. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Calls for Formulation of East African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister
Musalia Mudavadi today urged the business community in three East
African countries to draw investment guidelines in order to
promote regional investment.
</P>
<P>
Opening the East African Secretariat Joint Investment
Promotion Seminar here, the minister noted that an important
issue the seminar should address is the appropriate investment
guidelines designed to guide local people to invest
within the region.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the challenge to the business community in
Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda is to move away from the traditional
economic activities of producing commodities such as coffee, tea,
sisal, cotton or minerals for export.
</P>
<P>
To escape from the vagaries of price fluctuations in the
international commodity markets, Mudavadi stressed, "We must
shift our emphasis to non-traditional exports."
</P>
<P>
"We need to invest in food processing, production of
manufactured goods and production of high value goods and
services," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan minister said that the enlarged market in East
African region will enable the three countries to attract more
investment.
</P>
<P>
He urged the recently formed East African Business Council to
play an important role in identifying opportunities for
investments, markets for finished goods, services and raw
materials.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that over the last couple of years, the
three member countries had been implementing a series of economic
reform measures to facilitate regional trade and investments.
</P>
<P>
The three East African governments endeavor to create a
conducive environment for regional investment, he said, adding
that "It is the responsibility of the business community to take
up the challenges together with the opportunities the
co-operation has created."
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar is the first of the East African
Co-operation joint investment promotion seminar which will be
held in rotation in member countries.
</P>
<P>
Attending the seminar were representatives from the Kenya
Investment Promotion Center, the Uganda Investment Authority, the
Tanzania Investment Center and the Zanzibar Investment Promotion
Agency, and about 150 local private investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
