<HEADLINE> Zambian Government Urged to Increase Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Some Zambian parliament
members today urged the government to increase education
budgetary allocation to more than 15 percent by the year 2000
from the current nine percent.
</P>
<P>
Kasuka Mutukwa, Chairman of the Select Committee on Education,
Science and Technology, said education in Zambia is not
adequately funded and that the utilization of available resources
has not positively contributed to national development.
</P>
<P>
"Our committee, therefore, wishes to recommend that resource
allocation to education be increased to at least 15 percent of
the national budget by the year 2000," he said.
</P>
<P>
Independent parliament member Robert Sichinga warned that in
the 21st century countries lag behind in education, science and
technology will face stiff competition from other advanced
countries.
</P>
<P>
He called for a massive investment in education in order to
reduce the high level of illiteracy in the country.
</P>
<P>
Another independent parliament member, Crispin Sibetta said
the country has been robbed of highly energetic and educated
teachers who have migrated to neighboring countries in search for
greener pastures.
</P>
<P>
He said early retirement coupled with deplorable conditions of
service have forced highly qualified teachers out of the
education system in the country.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to improve the conditions of service
for teachers in rural areas by providing them with hardship
allowances, decent houses and promotion opportunities as a way of
attracting more teachers in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Education Minister Syamukayumbu Syamujaye conceded
that education in Zambia is the least funded in the southern
African region.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the government is making frantic
efforts to raise the standard of education.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government will ensure increased
enrollment in schools, quality education through the provision of
text books and equal opportunities in education for both sexes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
