<HEADLINE> UNDP: DPRK Needs Sustainable Support for Agricultural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The emergency response of the
donor community to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK) cannot provide a sustainable solution to the food shortage
in the country, said the United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
here today.
</P>
<P>
What DPRK needs, UNDP said, is a general rehabilitation of
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"The international community is doing a lot in North Korea,"
said Christian Lemaire, UNDP Resident Representative in DPRK. "But
the crisis will be ongoing if we keep conceiving aid as a
hand-out. We need funding and implementation of sustainable
practices if we are to help the country get back on its feet."
</P>
<P>
As one of the successful initiatives, UNDP said, the first
cooperation to rehabilitate the agricultural sector between DPRK
and the Republic of Korea will shift an initial 1.2-million-dollar
worth of heavy equipment directly from the South Korean port of
Inchon to DPRK's Nampo Port on November 22.
</P>
<P>
Other successful initiatives this year have included the
first-ever double crop program which was implemented on some
30,000 hectares of land and yielded 65,000 tons of grain. A
cooperation in the rehabilitation of agriculture has started
between DPRK and China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
