<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Put on Trial 38 Involved in Islamic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 21 (Xinhua) -- France will put on trial from
Monday in Paris 38 people, most of them Algerians or naturalized
immigrants, who were accused of running a logistic back-up network
for terrorists in Algeria, said judicial sources in Paris.
</P>
<P>
These people were arrested in August 1985, when French police
launched a campaign against terrorists after France was struck by
a wave of terrorist attacks claimed by the Algerian Islamic
militant group, the Armed Islamic Group (GIA).
</P>
<P>
All the accused could face 10 years in prison for "association
with wrongdoers in relations with a terrorist enterprise."
</P>
<P>
Most of the accused, who were from the region of Rhone-Alpes in
southeast France, were arrested after a home-made bomb was found
on a TGV bullet train from Lyon to Paris in August 1995.
</P>
<P>
Police tracked down the Islamist suspects in the Rhone-Alpes
region and discovered a Islamic support network spreading into
several European countries including Belgium, Germany, Italy and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
The network was involved in "recruitment of activists,
spreading information on GIA, looking for fund, arms and other
materials for the Algerian GIA guerrillas, their transportation
and the transportation of combatants toward Algeria and provision
of false government documents." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
