<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Dassault President Rejects Theory on Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Serge Dassault, the president of
the Dassault Industries group of France which makes Mirage and
Rafale combat aircraft, today described as "fiction" the theory
that a merger between his company and the state-run Aerospatiale
group will help compete with the Americans in airspace market.
</P>
<P>
In a television interview, Dassault said that he has nothing to
gain if the Dassault Aviation, an affiliate group of Dassault
Industrie, combines its activities with those of Aerospatiale,
which makes Airbus and ATR civilian planes.
</P>
<P>
"It is a fiction to think that one should put together the
civil with the military because the Americans are concentrated and
one should do the same," said Dassault.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist government of France supports a combination of
France's best high-tech companies, including airspace companies,
to compete with U.S. airspace giants such as Boeing-McDonnell
Douglas and Lockheed-Martin, which had experienced a series of
mergers lately.
</P>
<P>
"One should not do the same unless the industrialists have an
interest to do it," said Dassault, adding that he prefered to
"be small and gain money" and to have "good materials and
competent men." 
</P>
</TEXT>
