<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Congratulates Georgian President on Abkhazia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 21 (Xinhua) -- France today congratulated
Georgian President Edouard Shevardnadze on the agreement concluded
lately in Geneva between Georgia and Abkhazian separatists.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said that
much work remains to be done to obtain a global solution to the
conflict and to restore territorial integrity and sovereignty of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
"France can already congratulate the relaunch and primary
progress of the talks thanks to the efforts jointly made by the
United Nations, the Russian diplomacy and President Shevardnadze,
whose courageous initiatives have contributed to allowing this
resumption of dialogue between the two sides," she said.
</P>
<P>
France, Germany, Britain and the United States have played the
role of observers in the negotiations between Georgian government
and Abkhazians, while Russia played the role as a "facilitator."
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to establish a council of coordination on
security, refugees and economic issues.
</P>
<P>
From 3,000 to 10,000 people were estimated to have been killed
in the Georgia-Abkhazian conflict and 250,000 made refugees after
Abkhazian separatists declared independence from Georgia in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian government and Abkhazians reached a truce
agreement in May 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Stocks Enough Maize Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 21 (Zimbabwe) -- The Zimbabwe Agricultural
Commodity Exchange (ZIMACE) today ruled out rumors of
insufficient maize stocks on the market following speculative
economic situation and the unprecedented fall of local currency
last week.
</P>
<P>
In its review of weekly marketing trends, ZIMACE said maize
continued to be a major trader, with a wider variety of
commodities being sold than in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
"Despite rumours to the contrary, there appears to be
sufficient maize in the market with millers indicating they had
sufficient stocks until the New Year," ZIMMAC noted.
</P>
<P>
In fact, according to the agency, there had been a swing in
the market with more offers to sell maize than there were buyers
at present.
</P>
<P>
However, ZIMACE noted that this situation could change just as
quickly and producers and buyers needed to monitor the market
fairly closely.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ZIMACE said, although there had been problems with
the quality of some of this year's wheat crop, producers could
take comfort from the increasing number of bids being registered
for both undergrade and sample grade wheat.
</P>
<P>
"Prices for this quality of wheat are also increasing and it
would seem that there is definitely a market for it," it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
