<HEADLINE> China Dominates Chinese Chess World Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONGKONG, November 21, (Xinhua) -- Players from China and
Chinese Taipei took a solid lead in the men's and women's
individual competition after five rounds at the Fifth World
Chinese Chess Championships here Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the men's section, world runner-up Wu Guilin from Chinese
Taipei remained unbeaten through five rounds and topped the list
with 10 points.
</P>
<P>
Wu guilin held off his rivals with his delicate layout and
all-round skill, standing as a main obstacle for his
title-defending compatriot Lu Qin from the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Two-time world champion Lu shared the second slot with his
countryman Xu Yinchuan with nine points each.
</P>
<P>
In the women's pool, Lin Ye, a former Chinese national champion
but now represents Italy, ranks first with nine points from four
wins and one draw.
</P>
<P>
Gao Yi, 21, a debutee from China, has chalked up four straight
wins with a total of eight points.
</P>
<P>
The former champion Zhang Xinhuan of Singapore placed third,
 with a 2-2-1 record.
</P>
<P>
The nine-round event will wrap up on November 23. 
</P>
