<HEADLINE> World Sugar Production Forecast to Fall in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- World sugar production is
expected to fall to 122.8 million tons this year, 320,000 tons
less than last year, Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Czarnikow, a sugar market analyst, was quoted by the newspaper
as also reducing its forecast for global sugar consumption for
1998 from 124.37 million tons to 123.98 million tons, compared
with the expected 121.91 million tons for this year.
</P>
<P>
The sugar analyst said in its latest sugar review that sugar
production levels in the European Union countries have outstripped
forecasts earlier this year and its total beet crop is now put at
19.05 million tons, an increase of 1.07 million tons over last
year.
</P>
<P>
However, sugar production in Russia and Ukraine have slipped
back sharply and it forecast a combined production drop of 1.19
tons in east Europe.
</P>
<P>
It continued to forecast India's sugar production for this
season at 11.69 million tons, and said that India will need to
import sugar for its third-quarter supplies next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
