<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ogata Urges Bosnia to Allow Return of Minority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Ethnic minorities must be
allowed to return safely to Bosnia and Herzegovina, United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees Mrs Sadako Ogata said in a
statement issued here today.
</P>
<P>
"I was encouraged to see returnees rebuilding their houses, but
so far only a fraction of those who lost their homes during the
war have returned," said Ogata, who had a three-day visit to the
region recently.
</P>
<P>
"Next year must become the year of minority returns," Ogata
pointed out, saying that particular emphasis must be placed on the
return of ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued one month before the second
anniversary of the Dayton Peace Accord signed in Dayton, Ohio, on
November 21, 1995, which ended the four-year civil war in
Bosnia-Herzegovina. The war forced some 2.3 million Bosnians to
flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
Some 400,000 Bosnians returned both from abroad and within
Bosnia-Herzegovina since the Dayton Accord, according to UNHCR.
But the vast majority of them returned to areas controlled by
their own ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
There are still some 700,000 refugees and an additional 800,000
remain displaced within Bosnia-Herzegovina, most of whom are
unable to return to places where they would be in a minority,
UNHCR says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
