<HEADLINE> Albright: Russia not to Influence U.S. on Iraq Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia, though having
defused standoff on the weapons inspections by persuading Iraq
to back down, would not influence the United States in getting
sanctions on Baghdad to be lifted, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
There is "no quick answer" to the question of lifting the
sanctions on Iraq, Albright told ABC's "Good Morning America"
when asked if Russia could influence the United States in voting
for that.
</P>
<P>
"Throughout the last six and one-half years and during the
four years that I was at the U.N., the Russians did the same
thing. They would argue the case of lifting sanctions," she
said.
</P>
<P>
But "we always made it very clear, first of all, that the
United States would not agree until Saddam Hussein fulfilled his
obligations under the relevant sanctions resolutions, and
second, ultimately the rest of the Security Council agreed with
us."
</P>
<P>
In a separate interview with CNN, Albright thanked Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov for his mediation role in
breaking the deadlock of the weapons inspection crisis.
</P>
<P>
"What Mr Primakov has done was very useful. We appreciated
the work that Mr. Primakov had done," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
