<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 120,000 Kenyans Facing Starvation in Wajir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is to
airlift emergency food supplies and drugs to Wajir District in
Northeastern Province to curb a looming food shortage.
</P>
<P>
Wajir District Commissioner David Mutemi was quoted as saying
Thursday that more than 120,000 people are facing starvation in
the district due to the current floods.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the road between Nairobi and Wajir had been
heavily flooded by torrential rains in the past month, making it
difficult to transport food to the district.
</P>
<P>
John Koech, Minister of State in the Office of the President,
who is leading a national disaster management team to assess the
flood situation, said in Wajir that the district had been worst
hit by the heavy rains in the past one month in the East African
country.
</P>
<P>
He directed the National Cereal and Produce Board to
distribute the available 500,000 bags (90 kilograms per bag) of
maize to the needy families in the district.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi announced Wednesday that the
government had declared the Northeastern Province a flood
disaster zone.
</P>
<P>
The Mandera District of the disaster province are facing fuel
crisis with all government departments and other organizations
going to cease their operations in four days time due to lack of
fuel.
</P>
<P>
District Commissioner Richard Rakuomi told Kenya News Agency
today that out of the five filling stations in the district, only
one is supplying fuel while others have gone out of stock.
</P>
<P>
He noted that their tankers had stalled on the roads between
Isiolo and Mandera and between Garissa and Mandera as a result of
heavy rains which have hit the area in the last two months.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted a local businessman as saying today that his
efforts to import the commodity from neighboring countries by
road proved futile when his convoy of 10 tankers got stuck in
Somalia and three in Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
