<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Eritrea to Conduct Trade in U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Minister of Economic
Development and Cooperation Girma Birru said today business
transaction between Ethiopia and Eritrea will as of tomorrow be
conducted in U.S. Dr and other world-recognized hard currencies.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made here after Eritrea introduced its
own currency Nakfa on November 8 after using the Ethiopian
currency Birr since its independence in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the local press on the new business relationship
between the two countries, the Ethiopian minister said the two
countries have agreed on the new arrangement.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement has been necessitated, Birru said, as a result
of the different financial and trade policies prevailing in both
countries, which will pose problems on both economies under
different scheme than the one already agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
Beginning tomorrow, he said, transactions between Eritrea and
Ethiopia will be conducted through bank guarantee.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ethiopia's Ministry of Trade and Industry today
issued a directive regarding small cross-border business
activities along the Ethio-Eritrean border.
</P>
<P>
According to the directive, the value of commodities crossing
the border cannot exceed 2,000 Birr (about 294 US dollars). The
directive stipulates that any person intending to engage in small
cross-border trade should obtain licenses from the relevant
authorities.
</P>
<P>
This decision will not have a significant impact on the
balance of trade of both countries, the minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
