<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Wants All-Round Settlement to Cyprus: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan's Special Advisor for Cyprus Diego Cordovez said here today
that both he and the U.N. chief want to reach a comprehensive
settlement to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement at a press conference at the end of his
three-day fact-finding mission in Cyprus, during which he had
separate meetings with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez arrived here late Tuesday night for his first visit to
the island since he was named special Cyprus envoy by Kofi Annan
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez told reporters that he felt there was "historic
distrust" between the Greek and Turkish communities in Cyprus with
neither side believing that the other wants an agreement.
</P>
<P>
"The worst enemy of an agreement is distrust and distrust is
very high in this case," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official said he will visit the island in March,
immediately after February's presidential elections, to begin his
efforts for a settlement.
</P>
<P>
Both Clerides and Denktash agreed "very strongly" on his
March visit during which he will discuss the modalities of the
negotiations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez warned the two community leaders that increased
international interest in a Cyprus settlement will diminish if a
solution can not be reached in next year's peace effort.
</P>
<P>
"The two leaders have to understand that this concern of the
international community is not going to last forever," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy also expressed welcome to U.S. interest in a
settlement in Cyprus and said he depends on both the U.S. and the
European Union (EU) in his mission.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez chaired two rounds of direct talks between Clerides
and Denktash in New York and Switzerland this year in an effort
to break the deadlock in the U.N.-sponsored talks for the
reunification of the island in a bizonal, bicommunal federation.
</P>
<P>
The talks collapsed in Switzerland after Denktash declared he
would not attend further joint meetings unless the EU canceled its
plans to open entry negotiations with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
This eastern Mediterranean island has been split into the
Greek Cypriot-dominated south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled
north since 1974 when Turkish troops took over the northern third
of the island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez left here today for Athens, and then will go to Ankara
to meet with the government officials of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to hold talks on the Cyprus issue with
European Union Commissioner for External Relations Hans Van den
Broek in Brussels and the EU presidency envoy for Cyprus
Kester Heaslip in Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
