<HEADLINE> Survey Indicates Jobs Shortage for Ex-Welfare Recipients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Conference of Mayors
survey on welfare reform in 34 cities suggests a jobs shortage for
welfare recipients and lack of availability of child care and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
The survey found 13 cities responding to the question of job
availability suggest a shortage in the number of low-skill jobs
available for one-time welfare recipients seeking employment.
</P>
<P>
Detroit expects a shortfall of 75,303 jobs, Philadelphia 53,400
and Seattle 28,522 jobs to meet the demand of employment seekers,
according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
Other cities that will fall short of jobs include Boston with a
shortage of 9,990 jobs; St. Paul, Minnesota, 9,682; St. Louis,
6,734; and New Orleans, 6,763 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Many new low-skill jobs are in suburbs so transportation is a
problem because heavy concentrations of welfare recipients live in
the cities.
</P>
<P>
Welfare reform got its unofficial start in the early 1990s,
when states got permission to experiment with measures to nudge
recipients into the world of work.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton signed a sweeping bill, crafted by
Republicans in Congress, into law in the fall of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Government estimated 3.5 million people, about one-quarter of
all welfare recipients, have left the rolls over the last three
years as a result of an improved economy and the new law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
