<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Deputy PM Visits Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz arrived here this evening for a two-day visit to Syria,
the first by an Iraqi official of such level in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa received him at
Damascus International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Aziz told reporters that he was glad to visit
Damascus to brief the Syrian leaders on situation in Iraq and
Iraq's views on the future and to express his country's
appreciation of Syria's stance towards the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
Replying a question on the seven-year-old U.N. sanctions on
Iraq, he said "We hope that our brothers in all the Arab countries
would work to lift the sanctions."
</P>
<P>
The crippling sanctions were imposed after the 1990 Iraqi
invasion of Kuwait. The sanctions can only be lifted after
U.N. inspectors make sure that Iraq has eliminated all its weapons
of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
But a crisis rose when Iraq announced to deny entry to
U.S. members of the U.N. inspection team earlier this month and
the U.S. threatened to use force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
As for Iraq's agreement to allow the U.N. weapon inspectors
resume their work, Aziz said "I think the Iraqi problem was made
more clear for the world than it had been before the recent
UN-Iraqi standoff. Certainly when the problem becomes clear, there
are more chances for supporting our legitimate demands and lifting
the embargo on Iraq." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
