<HEADLINE> APEC Trade Ministers Narrow Trade Sectors for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, Canada, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Trade ministers and
senior officials from the 18 economies of the Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum today agreed to narrow down
trade sectors for early liberalization from 15 to eight sectors.
</P>
<P>
The trade ministers, who ended an informal session, will
present the results to the 9th ministerial meeting for selection.
The two-day meeting is to start in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
APEC senior officials concluded a two-day meeting Thursday and
prepared a list of 15 sectors for the trade ministers to choose
for early liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The sectors include environmental goods and services,
fisheries, forest products, gems and jewelry, oil-seeds,
chemicals, telecommunications, energy, food, rubber, fertilizers,
automotive standards, medical equipment and civil aircraft.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, APEC leaders agreed in Subic Bay of the Philippines
that ministers will identify sectors where early voluntary
liberalization will have a positive impact on trade, investment
and economic growth and submit recommendations to the leaders.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a list of 61 proposals came up at the senior
officials meetings and was narrowed down to 41 in Singapore in
October.
</P>
<P>
APEC members have not reached consensus on a single sector so
far because many are expected to protect their interests in
sensitive sectors.
</P>
<P>
Canada, host of this year's meeting, pursued a number of
priorities in early liberalization sectors ranging from primary
and manufactured goods.
</P>
<P>
"We have been in forefront efforts to identify fishery sector,
wood product, oil seeds and primary product material," a senior
Canadian official said.
</P>
<P>
But the Canadian proposal on fisheries was opposed by Japan.
</P>
<P>
The financial turmoil in Southeast Asia, another major subject
for discussions, casts shadows over the meetings, which aim at
liberalizing trade and investment on the Pacific rim.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, deputy finance ministers from Asia and the U.S.,
along with top officials from the International Monetary Fund
(IMF), agreed to a framework for regional cooperation to promote
financial stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The APEC, which was initiated in 1989, now groups Australia,
Brunei Darussalam, Canada, Chile, China, China's Hong Kong,
Indonesia, the Republic of Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand,
Papua New Guinea, the Philipines, Singapore, Chinese Taipei,
Thailand and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
