<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Tests CJTF Headquarters Command Capability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MUNSTER, Germany, November 21 (Xinhua) -- NATO Military
Committee Chairman Klaus Naumann today proclaimed the try-out of
the Combined Joint Task Force (CJTF) headquarters an "unqualified
success".
</P>
<P>
The military chief of the western military alliance gave the
high mark while addressing a press conference on the penultimate
day of the week-long trial of the command post.
</P>
<P>
All but two of the NATO member states participated in the trial
that was carried out in a fictitious scenario.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg and Iceland opted out. France and Spain, though not
yet back into the NATO integrated military command structure, took
part in the test.
</P>
<P>
The command post trial was the final phase of the preparation
of the formation of the CJTF headquarters. The year-long
operation cost NATO 1.7 million U.S. dollars, according to General
Wesley Clark who is the supreme allied commander in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the trial, codenamed Allied Effort '97, was to
design, exercise and evaluate information processing, coordinating
and tasking capabilities of the CJTF headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Experiences were drawn from NATO peace-keeping operations in
Bosnia-Herzegovina through its multinational Implementation Force
(IFOR) and Stabilization Force (SFOR).
</P>
<P>
Preliminary doctrines, structures, personnel and equipment
requirements and resource implications had to be considered and
plans formulated during the trial.
</P>
<P>
The concept of CJTF, which actually stands for multi-national
and multi-service task force, was first conceived in January 1994
and received endorsement in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
The concept marks an important step in NATO's adaptation to the
changing global security settings, especially beyond-NATO-area
peace operations.
</P>
<P>
The Allied Effort '97 trial was based on a made-up peninsula
named Gem that extends into the Indian Ocean from the southeast
corner of Africa.
</P>
<P>
A NATO-led peace implementation force (PFOR), under the command
of the CJTF headquarters manned by a 2,200-strong staff, was
called upon by a United Nations mandate to separate the two
warring nations on the southern tip of the peninsula and guard a
50-kilometer-wide demilitarized zone in between.
</P>
<P>
Build-up of the CJTF command post started on November 3 with a
short notice and the trial that went underway last Sunday tested
such areas as personnel, intelligence, operation, logistics,
planning, communications and control, budget and finance,
relations with the civilian and engineering.
</P>
<P>
The NATO Military Committee chief described the CJTF
headquarters as a separate yet inseparable command within the NATO
command structure.
</P>
<P>
NATO is planning a sea-based trial run for CJTF following the
land-based trial in Munster. The next trial, to be known as
Strong Resolve '98, can be conducted as early as next March.
</P>
<P>
Asked when CJTF will be ready for operation, General Naumann
said that the multi-national and multi-service task force should
be ready to act between mid-1998 and the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
