<HEADLINE> Ecological Meeting Draws Blueprint for Caspian Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, November 22 (Xinhua) -- A regional meeting has worked
out a blueprint for the ecological protection of the land-locked
Caspian Sea, the weekly Panorama said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, sponsored by the United Nations Development
Program and an international foundation, was called to coordinate
the implementation of the Caspian Sea ecological protection
program put forward by Kazakhstan two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Representative in Kazakhstan, Herbert Berstok, said
the World Bank and the international foundation will fund the
plan, which will be implemented from next fall.
</P>
<P>
The rising of water level in the Caspian Sea has flooded 8
million hectares of land in Azerbaijan, causing 12 billion
U.S. dollars in damage. It also inundated seven settlements and
some 630,000 hectares of grain field in Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The weekly, however, did not say what had caused the rise of
water level. 
</P>
