<HEADLINE> Excessive Supply of Beijing Office Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Rental fees for office space
in the Chinese capital are expected to fall with the completion of
a large number of office towers by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, office towers in the city had total
floor space of over 1.5 million sq.m., with the figure expected to
rise by as much as one million sq.m. by early next year, according
to the Information Center of the Ministry of Construction.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources note that as much as 35 percent of available
office space has remained idle this year, and the proportion will
rise by five percentage points in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Rental fees for one sq.m. of office space hit a record 78 US
dollars in early 1995, but fell to 63 US dollars at the end of
last year. The figure plummeted further to 39 US dollars in the
first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
High-rise office buildings are mainly located in downtown
districts such as Chaoyang, Eastern City and Western City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
