<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Buy Patriot Missiles Worth 300 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has sealed a
contract with the U.S. Reython Company to buy 300 million
U.S. dollars worth of Patriot missiles.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. company is also obliged to invest in a joint venture
with Kuwait to set up an alumium smelter under Kuwait's offset
program, an official of the Executive Bureau for Offset Operations
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Mazen Madouh, whose bureau is affiliated with the Finance
Ministry, was speaking on the sidelines of an offset and economic
development conference.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's Offset Program requires any foreign arms supplier
winning a contract worth more than 1 million Kuwaiti dinars (3.3
million U.S. dollars) from the oil-rich emirate to reinvest 30
percent of the contract's value in Kuwait or Kuwait's ventures
abroad.
</P>
<P>
The program is mainly aimed at getting back some of the funds
which have poured out in defense contracts signed with mainly
Kuwait's western allies since it started a massive rearmament plan
following the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The aluminum project is one of the largest projects approved
under the Offset Program with an designed annual capacity of
230,000 tonnes of aluminum.
</P>
<P>
Reython Company is obliged to invest some 100 million
U.S. dollars in Kuwait for eight years, but the fund might not be
totally invested in the smelter project, Nadouh said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has so far received 1.5 billion U.S. dollars of
investment obligations from its arms suppliers under its Offset
Program launched in 1992, according to the Offset official.
</P>
<P>
A total of 17 companies, almost exclusively defense companies
have signed offset agreements with Kuwait. France and Britain
also have offset projects in the country.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Finance Minister Nasser Abdullah Al-Rudhan told Kuwaiti
parliament in September that Kuwait currently had seven major
offset projects either being implemented or under formation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
