<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Launches African Education Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 22 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of
African Unity (OAU) today formally launched the decade of
education in Africa (1997-2006).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the launching ceremony here, Salim Ahmed Salim,
Secretary General of the OAU, said for many years now, Africa has
been characterized by the high level of illiteracy among its
peoples.
</P>
<P>
"Africa has an illiteracy rate of 56 percent which is said to
be the highest in the world. In the early 1990s, 18 million girls
in Africa and 12 million boys were without access to primary
education," he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, about 26 million African girls are reported to be
out of schools and most of them are in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the declaration of the ministerial meeting on the
education of girls held in Ouagadougou in 1996, the figure is
likely to increase to 36 million by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Salim described the eighties as " the lost decade for Africa",
and said that "the launching of the education decade provides yet
another opportunity for all of us to re-dedicate ourselves to the
objectives of promoting education in our continent and ensuring
education for all."
</P>
<P>
"Education should not only liberate the minds of our youth and
adults, but it should equip them with knowledge, skill and
appropriate orientation to cope with the rapidly changing
technology which is becoming a major factor throughout the
world," Salim said.
</P>
<P>
He called on Africans to leave no stone unturned to make sure
that this decade delivers its promises.
</P>
<P>
Salim also disclosed that a program of action is to be
formulated by a conference of African ministers of education
which will take place in Durban, South Africa from April 20 to
24, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Lift Ban on Imports of Iranian Pistachio Nuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission is
considering lifting a ban it imposed last September on the imports
of Iranian pistachio nuts provided that certain conditions are met.
</P>
<P>
The European Report issued today said that a commission
decision on lifting the ban is expected to be taken early next
month.
</P>
<P>
The imports of Iranian pistachio nuts were suspended after
several consignments were found containing toxic substance which
is usually caused by mould forming on damp cargoes.
</P>
<P>
Inspectors from several EU member states found that in some
cases contamination levels of carcinogenic aflatoxin were between
11 and 400 parts per billion (ppb), as against a permissible limit
of 2 ppb for pistachio nuts ready for direct consumption.
</P>
<P>
Permissible limit for raw pistachio nuts not yet intended for
direct consumption should not exceed 5 ppb.
</P>
<P>
The commission imposed the ban on a food hygiene ruling that
gives it the right to take safeguard measures if a hygiene problem
likely to create a serious risk to human health appears or spreads
on the territory of a non-EU country.
</P>
<P>
Exports of pistachio nuts are Iran's third main source of
foreign currency after hydrocarbons and carpets and earned the
country 500 million U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
EU member states imported 90,000 of the 130,000 tons of
pistachio nuts produced by Iran last year.
</P>
<P>
The EU is the world's leading importer of pistachio nuts,
followed by the Gulf states and the countries in Far East.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haikou Tourism Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Haikou, the capital of south
China's Hainan Province, has completed two of four major tourism
projects, with work on the remaining projects progressing smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The five-star Hainan Wenhua Grand Hotel recently entered
operations. The Sino-Singaporean project was constructed at a cost
of over 77 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Holiday Beach Marine World, constructed by the Hainan
Fangyuan Group and Haikou Zhongda Group, has also entered
operations.
</P>
<P>
The Hainan Xingbao Group also plans to invest more than 300
million yuan to construct the Huaxia Shenzhou Leisure Village, and
the Hainan Shengshi Tourism Development Co. Ltd. will invest over
one billion yuan to develop the Huaxia Marine World.
</P>
<P>
Haikou's tourism sector has witnessed rapid development. 1.21
million tourists visited the city in the first eight months of
this year representing a 17.9 percent increase on last year's same
period.  
</P>
