<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computerization of China's Financial Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 22 (Xinhua) -- While computerized financial
transactions can be completed within seconds, it has taken China's
major financial cities and towns some 10 years to accomplish the
same task.
</P>
<P>
China introduced a nationwide computerized system to commercial
banks and department stores almost a decade ago, with the
framework for an advanced network currently in place, according to
sources attending this week's financial seminar held in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Some 320 medium- to large-sized computer systems were
operational in China by the end of last year, as well as 4,000
smaller systems, 12,000 automated teller machines (ATM) and
80,000-odd point-of-sales terminals department stores.
</P>
<P>
Some 110,00 branches of Chinese commercial banks have been
computerized, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China (PBOC), the nation's central bank,
has installed a ground station and 648 remote stations for a
satellite communications network specially designed for financial
institution. The network provides links to all Chinese cities and
a number of developed counties.
</P>
<P>
A financial data exchange network jointly funded by major
commercial banks and the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications,
which went online in 1996, currently links 198 major Chinese
cities.
</P>
<P>
China has recorded major progress in computerizing bank account
settlements within cities, with facilities in more than 400 cities
currently providing rapid and convenient services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
