<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yamaichi Securities Considers Closing Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Yamaichi Securities Co., one of
Japan's "Big Four" brokerage houses is considering a voluntary
shutdown because of severe financial problems, according to press
reports.
</P>
<P>
Yamaichi, with debts of about 3 trillion yen (about 23.9
billion dollars), said it will make a final decision by Monday on
whether to terminate operations about 100 years after foundation.
</P>
<P>
If Yamaichi declares bankruptcy, it will be the biggest
collapse of a Japanese company since World War II.
</P>
<P>
Yamaichi finally gave up after its main clients canceled mutual
fund contacts with the brokerage, which resulted in a severe cash
crunch, industry sources said.
</P>
<P>
The cancellation is attributed to Yamaichi's worsening business
performance, a sharp drop in stock price and the downgrading of
its bonds early this month.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an emergency news conference, Atsushi Nagano,
director general of the Finance Ministry's Securities Bureau, said
Yamaichi is projected to have more than 200 billion yen (about 1.6
billiond dollars) in unlisted hidden debts.
</P>
<P>
But he said the situation is "not a serious one" because the
brokerage has no capital deficit, with about 430 billion yen
(about 3.4 billion dollars) in its capital account.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry and the Bank of Japan (BOJ) will provide
Yamaichi with rescue loans so that the company's clients are
protected.
</P>
<P>
Yamaichi's image was seriously tarnished by an infamous
financial scandal in Japan earlier this year involving payoffs to
a "sokaiya" corporate racketeer.
</P>
<P>
Yamaichi is likely to negotiate a liquidation scheme for
voluntary closure with the Finance Ministry, the central bank and
major commercial banks, industry sources said.
</P>
<P>
Under a voluntary closure arrangement, a securities company is
required to repay cash and securities to its customers and
liquidate its assests before shutting itself down.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1897, Yamaichi is a brokerage with the longest
history among Japan's four biggest securities firms that also
include Nomura Securities Co., Daiwa Securities Co. and Nikko
Securities Co.
</P>
<P>
Yamaichi's move follows the collapse of two major financial
institutions -- Sanyo Securities and Hokkaido Takushoku Bank.
</P>
<P>
Financial analysts said the collapse of several large financial
institutions is an indication that Japan's financial industry is
undergoing a major restructuring ahead of a so-called Big Bang
deregulation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0070 </DOCNO>
