<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inaugural Asian Hockey Federation Cup Kicks off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 22 (Xinhua) -- The inaugural Men's Asian
Hockey Federation Cup kicked off here Saturday with six
participating teams vying for one berth in the 1999 Asian Cup.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Taipei, Sri Lanka, Oman, Macao, Singapore, Uzbekistan
and host Hong Kong (China) will compete in the tournament,
introduced specially for the low-standard teams in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The idea was brewed out by the Hong Kong Hockey Association
(HKHA) at the 1994 Asian Hockey Federaton Congress.
</P>
<P>
HKHA believed this would encourage those Asian countries and
regions that are less competitive to gain experience and catch up
the first rate teams such as Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
Prior to 1997, the major international field hockey tournaments
available for Asian countries and regions were the Asian Games and
the Asian Cup, both held every four years.
</P>
<P>
While the strong teams are able to get enough sponsorship for
their solid programs, the weak teams have been suffering a lot as
their national associations couldn't make their ends meet.
</P>
<P>
To take this into consideration, AHF has voted to stage the
Men's and Women's Asian Federation Cup tournaments, and
commissioned HKHA to host the inaugural Men's AHF Cup.
</P>
<P>
AHF also decided the winners of the current tournament would be
invited to the Asian Cup, which was postponed to 1999 to
accommodate the new tournaments.
</P>
<P>
The inaugural Women's Asian Hockey Federation Cup will be held
on December 4-14 this year in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Taipei, Malaysia, Kazakhstan, Sri Lanka, Thailand,
Hong Kong (China) and host Singapore will take part. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
