<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haihe River Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 22 (Xinhua) -- China will invest 35.8 billion
yuan (4.47 billion US dollars) over the next 12 years to control
water pollution in the Haihe River Valley, according to sources
from the State Bureau of Environment Protection (SBEP).
</P>
<P>
The key environmental protection project will be the second the
nation has launched for a river. The first one was for the Huaihe
River.
</P>
<P>
Zang Yuxiang, deputy director of the SBEP Department of
Pollution Control, said the project will guarantee potable water
for Beijing, Tianjin and various other medium- to large-sized
cities, and will improve water quality for both industrial and
agricultural use. He said the project will also lead to the
overall ecological improvement and increase of water resources in
the area.
</P>
<P>
Seven key pollution control projects, including efforts to
protect the Guanting and Panda reservoirs, two important water
resources for Beijing and Tianjin, will by carried out.
</P>
<P>
Zang said that projects to tackle the Zhanghe and Weihe rivers
and the Nanyun Canal are expected to ease serious water pollution
in the provinces of Hebei, Henan and Shandong and areas along
rivers flowing through Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The water quality in the Haihe River Valley is expected to
fulfill state standards by the year 2010, according to Zang.
</P>
<P>
The Haihe River Valley, which covers 318,000 square kilometers,
encompasses Beijing and Tianjin, and six provinces including
Hebei, Henan and Shandong.
</P>
<P>
Some 11.7 million tons of waste and polluted water, or 12
percent of the national total, has been discharged into the Haihe
River Valley in recent years, a level second only to the Yangtze
River Valley.
</P>
<P>
Per capita water resources in the area account for only
one-sixth of the national average due to serious water pollution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Section of the Wujiang River Harnessed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Five years of efforts to
harness the Chongqing Section of the Wujiang River in southwest
China have expanded the section's handling capacity to passenger
and cargo vessels rated at 200 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Wujiang River, which flows from Weining County, Guizhou
Province, and empties into the Yangtze River in Fuling near
Chongqing, is one of the eight major tributaries along the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
Shipping along the Wujiang River has developed slowly due to
the river's rapid currents.
</P>
<P>
Sine the end of 1991, the local government has invested 42
million yuan to upgrade the navigatable section from Gongtan to
Fuling. The effort included the extensive demolition of reefs,
dredging channels, and building embankments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
