<HEADLINE> Nigeria Releases S.Leonean POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, November 22 (Xinhua) Nigeria's contigent attached to
western Africa's peace keeping force (ECOMOG), has released 28
Sierra Leonean prisoners of war (POW) Friday, senior navy
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Director of Defence Administration, Sammy Davies said that the
ceremony took place at Tagrin, three miles west of the Lungi
International Airport where the Nigerian troops are based.
</P>
<P>
The POWS were captured during series of clashes between
Nigerian and Sierra Leone forces at Jui, 13 miles east of the
capital and at the International Airport, 10 miles across the
Sierra Leone estuary.
</P>
<P>
The released prisoners include five soldiers, eight policemen,
six civilians, six former rebel combatants, Davies said.
</P>
<P>
One of the released, Tamba Musa, a former rebel combatant
said, "The experience was frightful. The Nigerians at First
tortured me with cigarette burns and later they used their
bayonets to open wounds on my back and then poured iodine into
them."
</P>
<P>
Musa said he was captured early July during an RUF attack on
Nigerian troops position near the airport.
</P>
<P>
Asked about his reaction to the peace agreement and the call
for a cessation of hostilities, Musa said, "It is a good sign. We
are all West Africans and we should be cementing our relationship
rather than fighting among ourselves. I hope the Nigerians will
realise that you cannot influence people through fighting. "
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
