<HEADLINE> Changing Focus of Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 22 (Xinhua) -- China's central and western
regions have emerged as the focus of foreign investment since the
the government shifted its emphasis to the development of related
areas.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors signed 35 contracts and 34 letters of intent
during the seminar on development in central and western China
which ended today, involving total investments of over 2.76
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Related projects cover wide-ranging sectors, including
telecommunications, transportation, energy, agriculture,
machine-building, finance, real estate, tourism and commercial
sectors.
</P>
<P>
A Taiwan company will join hands with the Wuhan Economic and
Technological Development Zone to establish a high-tech
development base which will be constructed at a cost of 400
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Central and western China are home to 88.7 percent of the
nation's total land, 60 percent of proven mineral resources, 70
percent of forest coverage and 64 percent of total manpower.
</P>
<P>
The four-day seminar attracted over 1,000 businessmen from 38
countries and regions including the United States, Japan, France
and Britain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
