<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Boost Investment in Small Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
set aside 125 million ECU (141 million U.S. dollars) for its
high-growth and technology-oriented small and medium-sized
enterprises (SMEs).
</P>
<P>
The special investment, known as European Technology Facility
(ETF), will be provided by the European Investment Bank (EIB) and
managed by the European Investment Fund (EIF), according to the
European Report issued today.
</P>
<P>
The ETF management agreement was signed Thursday in Luxembourg
by EIB President Sir Brian Unwin and EIF Financial Committee
Chairman Gerbrand Hop.
</P>
<P>
The 125 million ECU for creation and development of SMEs will
be drawn from the EIB's annual surpluses over the next three years
in specialized venture capital funds.
</P>
<P>
Together with increased lending in the sectors of health,
education, urban renewal, environment and trans-European networks,
the new investment constitutes a key part of the Amsterdam Special
Action Program the EIB launched earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The EIB president said the new fund will help stimulate EU's
employment through investment-led growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
