<HEADLINE> China to See Major Reduction in Steel Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 22 (Xinhua) -- The work force for China's
iron and steel sector will be slashed from 3.3 million workers in
1996 to 2.6 million by the end of this century, according to the
Ministry of Metallurgical Industry.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the ministry implemented a policy of retaining main
operations and separating auxiliary functions in order to raise
productive forces.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year alone, 786 auxiliary units
employing 835,000 people were segregated from 51 iron and steel
works.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for 1996 show that the industry earned profits of
26.2 billion yuan from subsidiary production activities.
</P>
<P>
The ministry plans to raise the profit level of subsidiary
production some 30 percent by the year 2000. 
</P>
