<HEADLINE> Australian Olympic Medallist Failed in Drug Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, November 22, (Xinhua) -- Australian Olympic runner-up
Scott Miller faces a three-month ban after he has tested positive
for taking marijuana, a banned substance, his lawyer said on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The test was made some month ago when Miller was out of
training with a shoulder injury,we will be defending it
vigorously," said Chris Murphy.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old swimmer, who won the silver of the 100-meter
butterfly at Atlanta Olympics, will face a three-month suspension
if found guilty.
</P>
<P>
AOC president John Coates said on Saturday that three athletes
had failed in drug tests recently, but he would not name them or
their sports.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Olympic Committee (AOC) on Friday beefed up its
fight against drugs by ordering its 41-member sports federations
to introduce a tougher anti-doping policy.
</P>
<P>
As part of the objective, any doping offenses which occur
within the Olympic movement will be heard by the Court of
Arbitration for Sport in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The drug-users will be banned for two years as a maximum
penalty from December 1.
</P>
<P>
The new policy will not apply to Miller because his case
occured earlier than the introduction. 
</P>
