<HEADLINE> Soeharto Given Highest Award by Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 22 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today invested visiting Indonesian President Soeharto
with South Africa's highest award to foreign citizens, the Order of
Good Hope.
</P>
<P>
Mandela conferred the Order of Good Hope, class one, grand cross
(gold) on a beaming Soeharto in a citation ceremony held at Mandela's
Cape Town residence, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The award was made in recognition of Soeharto's "invaluable
contribution" to the promotion of friendly and mutually beneficial
relations between the two countries, Nicholas Haysom, a legal adviser
in the president's office, said in the citation speech.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said the award was also a token of respect and appreciation
from the South African government and its people.
</P>
<P>
"President Soeharto has been a long-standing supporter of South
Africa's struggle for democracy and made an important contribution to
this struggle in international and regional forums."
</P>
<P>
Soeharto had demonstrated his solidarity with the people of South
Africa by ensuring that Indonesia had stringently applied sanctions
against South Africa during the apartheid era, Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
On receiving the award, Soeharto said he regards the conferring of
the order not only as a personal honor but for all of the people of
his country.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that both South Africa and Indonesia are called upon to
participate in the creation of a world order based on independence,
abiding peace and social justice, especially when we take into account
that next year South Africa will host the 12th summit of the
Non-Aligned Movement," Soeharto said.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto arrived in South Africa Thursday for a three-day state
visit. He is due to leave the country later today for Mexico and
Canada, where he will attend a meeting of the Asia pacific Economic
Cooperation forum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
