<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The European Union's extraordinary summit on jobs held in
Luxembourg ended Friday evening with the heads of state and
government agreeing upon a modest consensus: offering training
to 20 percent of the unemployed, harmonizing the way to count
unemployment and learning from each other the efficient methods to
fight unemployment. Each country of the European Union will also
give each of its unemployed youth and chronically unemployed
people a new chance to start.
</P>
<P>
-- A great part of Eastern Africa, from Djibouti to Kenya
through Ethiopia, and above all, Somalia, is flooded because of
torrential rains which are continuing without ceasing for one
month. In the most affected zone, between the River Juba and River
Shebelle in southern Somalia, 1,343 people have been killed by the
flood. France, after debating whether to mobilize the 3,200
French soldiers stationed in Djibouti, now prefers to provide
rescue aid to Ethiopia and Djibouti rather than Somalia, which is
considered a no man's land for humanitarian actions.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- In the wake of the European Union job summit in Luxembourg
and while the Socialist Party opened its congress in Brest, Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin said on Friday that there is now a ``real
awareness by Europeans of the need to face up to the problem of
massive unemployment.'' He congratulated the action of his
government on the development of talks on 35-hour working week
plan and on creating jobs for the youths.
</P>
<P>
-- General Paul Kagame, Vice President of Rwanda whose
misunderstanding with France started in 1992, revealed in an
interview with Le Figaro the story about his arrest five years ago
by French police in Paris, when he was chief of the Tutsi rebellion
in his country. He said that French Foreign Ministry officials
warned him at the time: ``If you don't stop the fight, you will not
see your family again, because all will be massacred.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
