<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Warns Against New Scramble for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has rejected to joint
initiative for African intervention force by the United States,
Britain and France, describing it as an attempt to sideline the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and divide the continent.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the just-concluded 7th ordinary session of the OAU
Mechanism for Conflict Prevention,Management and Resolution,
Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi warned that the plan would
render OAU's mechanism for conflict resolution impotent.
</P>
<P>
The attempt by some members of the international community to
divide Africa into Anglophone and Francophone peacekeepers is
unacceptable, Ikimi said.
</P>
<P>
The essence of the initiative, according to Ikimi, is to
"begin a new repartitioning of Africa into spheres of influences
and interests and thereby weaken the existing OAU authority".
</P>
<P>
The minister said that any initiative outside the African
continent must be implemented within the existing OAU mechanism,
adding that "it must be transparent and non-selective. It must
respond to the collective consensus of our leaders, our peoples
and our organizations."
</P>
<P>
Ikimi explained that Nigeria is not opposed to training of
African soldiers from individual African countries under
bilateral arrangements, but called on African leaders to be
cautious on extra-African initiatives.
</P>
<P>
It is noted that 7-10 African battalions are expected to be
trained by the U.S. special force, which has already begun the
mission, in order to strengthen the capacity of those selected
countries to participate in U.N. peacekeeping operation in Africa
and elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
