<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 22 (Xinhua) -- General Secretary of the
Communist Party of India (Marxist) Harkishan Singh Surjeet today
said that a mid-term election to Parliament appeared to be the
only solution to the present political uncertainty, created by the
Congress demand to drop the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam (DMK)
ministers from the Gujral government.
</P>
<P>
The Jain Commission report, tabled before Parliament here on
Thursday, had not indicted Tamil Nadu Chief Minister and DMK
President M. Karunanidhi for the conspiracy leading to former
prime minister Rajiv Gandhi's killing in 1991, he said.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the Congress for demanding the removal of DMK
ministers even before the Jain Commission report was discussed in
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
"It does not appear possible at present that the Congress will
climb down from its demand for removal of the DMK ministers,"
Surjeet told reporters in Bhopal city of Madhya Pradesh in central
India.
</P>
<P>
The present political climate of instability was unlikely to
change even after a mid-term poll, he said, adding that it would
be difficult to say now whether the political fog at the Center
would be cleared during the winter session of Parliament.
</P>
