<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Draw Up 12-Point Action Plan to Keep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 22 (Xinhua) -- The proposed National
Economic Action Council (NEAC), an advisory body to the government
on economic matters, will draw up a 12-point action plan in its
efforts to keep the economy on track, Malaysian Information
Minister Mohamed Rahmat said today.
</P>
<P>
The plan includes cost-saving measures, promoting use of local
products, boosting the competitive edge of Made-In-Malaysia goods,
reducing imports and checking the outflow of the ringgit by
encouraging people to spend their holidays in the country,
according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
"In our efforts to keep the economy on track, some of the
measures may not go down well with the people but everybody need
to make sacrifices," he was quoted by the Malaysian national news
agency Bernama as telling reporters in Johor Baharu, some 370
kilometers southeast from here.
</P>
<P>
He said that under the action plan, the people should switch to
a new lifestyle by adopting cost-saving measures and giving
preference to locally-manufactured products.
</P>
<P>
The people, who have enjoyed the country's prosperity in the
past 10 years, were left with no choice but to support the
government's programs to rejuvenate the economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that this time, the economic problems faced by the
country were serious as the ringgit and the stock market had been
attacked by currency speculators and manipulators.
</P>
<P>
The NEAC was proposed by the United Malays National
Organization, the largest component party of the coalition
National Front, and endorsed by all the other 13 component parties
of the Front led by Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
The NEAC, to be chaired by Mahathir, will be set up next month,
comprising ministers whose portfolios were related to the economy
and representatives from the manufacturing, export, banking and
finance sectors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
