<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean President Departs for APEC Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam today left for the fifth annual unofficial summit of
the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) in Vancouver,
Canada.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day session scheduled to begin on November 24,
Kim and leaders from 17 other APEC members will discuss ways to
develop infrastructure in the world's fast-growing region.
</P>
<P>
Other topics include cooperation to stablize the region's
currencies and foreign exchange markets, and to monitor progress
in liberalizing trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
APEC leaders will also evaluate the effect of trade
liberalization, find ways to preserve the environment and
accelerate the wider commercial use of Internet-based trading.
</P>
<P>
On the second day of the meeting, Kim will give a keynote
speech on the APEC-wide cooperation on infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the meeting, Kim plans to hold individual
meetings with APEC leaders.
</P>
<P>
The president said here earlier today that he will seek support
from Japanese and U.S. counterparts and cooperation with other
leaders to overcome the nation's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ban Ki-moon, senior presidential secretary for foreign affairs
and national security, said Kim's main goal will be to urge
Asia-Pacific economic powers to join hands in helping troubled
member countries, including South Korea, out of their crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kim will explain Seoul's plan to revive the economy in
individual meetings with APEC leaders, including Chinese President
Jiang Zemin and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president will seek the understanding of APEC leaders to
ensure peace and stability on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
He will also highlights the macroeconomic soundness of the
South Korean economy and South Korea's flexible policy responses
to economic and financial challenges, with the aim of enhancing
foreign confidence in the South Korean economy, Ban said.
</P>
<P>
South Korean officials predicted that the APEC leaders, who
will discuss the emerging financial crisis in Asia and the world
as well, will adopt a declaration to make efforts to cope with the
regional and global financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kim is scheduled to return to Seoul on November 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
