<HEADLINE> UN Special Inspectors Resume Work in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Arms inspectors working with
the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) on dismantling
Iraqi weapons of mass destruction resumed their normal work here
this morning.
</P>
<P>
The six permanent weapons inspection teams as well as the air
reconnaissance group the includes helicopters resumed operation
today, an unidentified Iraqi official told the Iraqi News Agency.
</P>
<P>
These teams left here this morning in different times heading
for sites marked for inspection and the Iraqi authorities offered
all necessary facilities.
</P>
<P>
Today's development followed the diplomatic solution to a
three-week standoff between the U.N. and Iraq, which expelled
American inspectors in order to draw world attention to its demand
for the lifting of seven-year-old crippling sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The teams returned to Iraq on Friday after Baghdad had
officially told the Security Council its agreement to the
resumption of the work of UNSCOM with all its members, including
the Americans, taking part. 
</P>
</TEXT>
