<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industry Executives Predict Big Day for E-Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Internet will have
as much an impact as the Industrial Revolution, but it will take
only 20 or 30 years instead of 200, the chief executive of a
leading U.S. software and hardware producer said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet is going to change everything, and at a pace we
have never seen before," said John Chambers, Chief Executive
Officer (CEO) of the northern California-based Cisco Systems, at
the end of the two-day Asia-Pacific Information Technology Summit.
</P>
<P>
Before an audience of some hundreds of U.S. and foreign
government officials and industry executives at the gathering, the
first of its kind, Chambers made his prediction: "Companies who
don't know how to use high-tech will be left behind."
</P>
<P>
However, he added, those that do know how to use will get rich
at cyberspace speed.
</P>
<P>
Founded seven years ago, Cisco now boasts annual sales of over
7 billion U.S. dollars, 40 percent of which are made over the Net.
</P>
<P>
The 3.2 billion dollars of electronic sales Cisco is expected
to achieve this year will approach what experts predicted a few
years ago to be today's total electronic commerce sales worldwide.
</P>
<P>
James Barksdale, CEO of Netscape Communications Corp.,
predicted that much of the business now done through the 300
billion product catalogs printed in the United States each year
will be transferred to the Net soon.
</P>
<P>
And he said as much as 80 percent of all purchases made have
the potential of being done over the Net.
</P>
<P>
While the United States is the leading innovator of Net
technologies and applications, Asian countries are well aware of
the potential benefits. Barksdale said 35 percent of Japan's
current seven million Internet users have used it for electronic
purchases.
</P>
<P>
In Australia, he said, 76 percent of enterprises will have
deployed Internet by the end of 1998, and that by the end of the
century, 95 percent of all residents of Singapore will be
connected by a high-speed, broadband network.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the conference also indicated that not all
businesses will benefit. One such industry seems to be the
newspaper business, said Australian media tycoon Rupert Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
Murdoch, whose empire includes newspapers, magazines,
television networks and the Twentieth Century Fox Film Corp., said
the future of many newspapers is threatened by a loss of their
lifeblood -- classified advertising -- which he said is
"vulnerable to attack by the Internet."
</P>
<P>
Only those papers that somehow can adapt, he said, will survive.
</P>
<P>
But he said information technology makes more winners than
losers, citing that it has created more than 9 million jobs in the
U.S. over the past decade, while destroying only 2.5 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Koreans Dominate Asian Speed Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 22 (Xinhua) -- South Koreans swept three gold
medals out of four while a Japanese stole the other one in the
first day of Asian Short-Track Speed Skating Championships here on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The competition reached a climax when all the six finalists
skated inside the listed Asian record in the men's 1,500 meters.
</P>
<P>
Lee Jung-Young of South Korea led all the way from the start,
clocking two minutes and 19.71 seconds, followed by his teammates
Lee Seung-Chan, 2:20.19, Kim Hyun-Chui, 2:20.39, Jung Suk-Ju,
2:21.47, and China's Wang Xuefeng, 2:21.63. A Japanese was
disqualified after the race.
</P>
<P>
The previous Asian record of 2:22.41 was set by South Korean
Kim Ki-Hoon in Japan four years ago.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Park Hye-Rim, 13, led a medal clean sweep in the
women's 1,500 meters, winning the title in 2:27.82, followed by
Park Hye-Won, 2:36.86, and Joo Min-Jin, 2:37.37.
</P>
<P>
South Korea also made a 1-2 finish in the women's 500m when Joo
Min-Jin romped home in 46.82 seconds, edging Park Hye-Rim's
46.93. China's Xu Jin took the third in 48.11.
</P>
<P>
Nishitani Takafumi of Japan was awarded with the men's 500m
title after the South Korea's Park Sae-Woo was disqualified later
for dangerous sprinting.
</P>
<P>
China's Wang Xuefeng settled for the runner-up spot in the
cliff-hanger, only 0.01 second behind Takafumi's 43.46.
</P>
<P>
About 40 skaters from Japan, South Korea, Mongolia, China's
Hong Kong and China are participating in the two-day
championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
