<HEADLINE> Indian PM Refuses to Comment on Current Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral today refused to comment on the current political crisis in
the country in the wake of the Congress' demand to dump Dravida
Munnetra Kazhagam (DMK) from the 14-party United Front (UF)
government on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A Jain Commission report, which was tabled before Parliament
here on Thursday, linked the DMK with the conspiracy in
assassination of Indian former prime minister Rajiv Gandhi in
1991.
</P>
<P>
Angry Congress MPs called on the Gujral government to sack the
DMK. Yet the core committee of the UF has rejected the Congress'
demand. Political impasse at the Center continues.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the country was facing a crisis at the
Calcutta airport, Gujral refused to comment on it.
</P>
<P>
He went to Calcutta today to take part in an official function
and would return to the capital soon after the function.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the country was heading for a mid-term poll,
he also refused to reply.
</P>
<P>
Political activities are expected to gain momentum this evening
when Gujral returned from Calcutta. UF spokesman Jaipal Reddy said
that doors have not been slammed for negotiations between the UF
and the Congress.  
</P>
</TEXT>
