<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Correlates Smog to Lung, Heart Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Medical researchers said
they have confirmed that more people are hospitalized for lung and
heart diseases as smog increases.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary results were released here today by the Kaiser
Foundation Research Institute (KFRI), which conducted a year-long
study based on more than 10,000 admissions to Kaiser Permanent
hospitals throughout 1995.
</P>
<P>
Hospital admissions for chronic respiratory disease were found
to rise by 7 percent for every 10-microgram increase in coarse
particles in the air. Admissions rose 3.5 percent for acute
respiratory illness and 3 percent for those with cardiovascular
disease.
</P>
<P>
"It is a surprisingly big increase in the number of patients
for a relatively small change in the level of pollution," said
Henry Gong, a professor of medicine and environmental health
specialist at University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
A number of previous studies have shown connections between smog
and various types of illness. One research project, released last
year, estimated that 64,000 people in major American cities may
die each year from lung or heart problems by inhaling particulates.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 90 percent of health effects studies relating to
smog have been conducted in the Eastern and Midwestern United
States, where there are significant sources of pollution not found
in Southern California. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
