<HEADLINE> Jordanian PM Condemns Terrorism, Backs Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister
Abdul-Salam Majali today condemned all forms of terrorism and said
killing of innocent people is unacceptable by all means.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Cairo-based Voice of Arabs Radio, Majali
maintained that Amman is fully standing beside Egypt in the face
of terrorism, urging world nations to cooperate in confronting the
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
A total of 62 foreign tourists and Egyptians were killed and
dozens wounded on Monday terrorist attack in Luxor, southern
Egypt. This worst ever attack in Egypt has drawn a chorus of world
condemnation.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the attack, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
sacked his interior minister to revamp security for tourists who
bring about some 3 billion U.S. dollars each other to the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
On the peace process, the Jordanian premier told the radio that
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is facing mounting
internal and external measures to change his government's policies
towards peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein of Jordan, during his stay in Washington this
week, held talks with U.S. officials on ways of taking clearer
measures to sidestep the current crisis hindering progress in
Arab-Israeli peace talks. 
</P>
