<HEADLINE> U.S. Willing to Help China Speed WTO Talks, says Barshefsky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States is willing
to join the efforts of China to speed the negotiations on China's
entry into the WTO, U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky
said today.
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky made the remarks when she met here with Wu Yi,
Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation,
said Chinese officials who were present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky noted the progress had been made in the field of
trade during the leaders' summit in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The United States spoke highly of China's decision to sign the
information technology agreement as soon as possible, Barshefsky
said.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Wu said that when Chinese President Jiang
Zemin visited the U.S. recently, both leaders expressed the hope
in the joint statement that the process of China's entry into the
WTO be quickened.
</P>
<P>
And President Clinton indicated that his country will do its best
to help China join the WTO, Wu said, adding that the talks today
should focus on how to turn the leaders' wishes into action.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed in detail the framework of a package of
market access, which includes issues such as tariffs and
non-tariff measures, information technology agreement and service
trade.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers agreed that Jiang's successful visit to the
U.S. put new vigor into the negotiations on China's entry into
the WTO.
</P>
<P>
They also held that China's recent package of market access
laid the basis for both sides to end bilateral negotiations on
this issue.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers are here to attend the APEC meetings.
</P>
</TEXT>
