<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Subsides Slowly: Geologist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have found that
Bangladesh is subsiding slowly, Bangladesh's English weekly
magazine Independent reported today.
</P>
<P>
The discovery was made by German marine geologist Dr. Hermann
Kudrass, who is now heading a 25-member scientific research team
on board the German research ship of RV Sonne in the Bengal Bay.
</P>
<P>
The German research ship, equipped with modern drilling
equipment, is studying the natural and climatic changes which
have taken place in the Bengal Bay during the last 100 years or
more, the magazine quoted Kudrass as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We'll work on sediment balance in the sea, cyclone history and
subsidence position," he said.
</P>
<P>
The research, which started on November 17, will also look into
sea warming or sea level rise, the geologist said.
</P>
<P>
"If there is sea warming, there will be sea level rise. So
you'll have to be prepared for consequent changes," he said,
refusing to make any prediction.
</P>
<P>
The current research work is a follow-up of a 1994 survey. It
is being carried out under a agreement between Geological Survey
of Bangladesh and Geological Survey of Germany, and with the
assistance from the German Ministry of Research and Technology.
Five geologists from Bangladesh are participating in the research.
</P>
<P>
"You know, Bangladesh is subsiding slowly and our second task
will be to have as accurate an estimation as possible of the rate
and process of subsiding," he added.
</P>
<P>
The research may require at least one year to process all the
data and finalize a report, the German geologist said. "We've a
plan to hold an international seminar in Dhaka on the research
findings within one year".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Beats Japan in World Volleyball Grand Champions Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Asian Champion China overcame a
first set down to defeat host Japan 3-1 in the fourth round of the
men's competition at the current world volleyball grand champions
cup tournament here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
China improved its record to 2-2 and assured its place among
the top-four in the six-team men's competition, while Japan fell
to 1-3 with a sole victory over winless Australia.
</P>
<P>
After lossing the first set 15-8, the Chinese spikers stayed in
calm to fight neck to neck with their Japanese rivals at 11-all
till the set ran into the 25-minute time limitation and the
rally-point scoring system was applied.
</P>
<P>
Paced by Zheng Liang's quick spike over the net and Zhang
Xiang's powerful smashes behind the rear line, China made no
mistakes to clinch their last four points and set at 15-13.
</P>
<P>
With over-net blockings and smashes, China tamed the
never-say-die Japanese by taking the next two sets 15-12 15-11.
</P>
<P>
"We didn't show our best forms today but we stayed in calm when
trailing behind. We won with better blockings and higher fighting
spirits," said Chinese head coach Wang Jiawen after the tow-hour
game.
</P>
<P>
China's solid blockings gained them 17 points, the same as
their attacking smashing had produced.
</P>
<P>
"After we had a good start in the first set, we lost our rhythm
afterwards. China beat us by effective blockings and quick hits
from Zheng Liang and Lu Weizhong," said Japanese head coach
Futoshi Teramawari.
</P>
<P>
In a tough confrontation between European champion the
Netherlands and South American champion Brazil, the latter are
leading 15-9, 15-12, 13-15 in the first three set. The match is
not over yet now.
</P>
<P>
Cuba will takes on Australia in Saturday's last match later in
the evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
