<HEADLINE> 170 Milliom Dollars Needed to Boost Mozambique's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique needs 170 million
U.S. Dollars to boost its higher education by the end of the
century, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Arnaldo Nhavoto, Education Minister of Mozambique made the
statement at a symposium on higher education development held
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Apart from national and local expansion programs, the country
is to use Internet for its higher education development for the
remote areas, Nhavoto said.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique, with a population of 15.74 million, has five
universities, three of them are state universities, while the
other two are private schools in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
People have been urging the government to establish a
university in northern Mozambique, but the lack of money in the
under-developed area has hindered local government from meeting
their demand.
</P>
<P>
There are now 7,000 students at the three State universities,
while the two private universities are taking in very small
number of students.
</P>
<P>
The country has 1.7 million students at primary and middle
schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
