<HEADLINE> Uganda Tightens Security to Protect Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Uganda army forces and local
defense units are to be deployed along Sudan-Uganda border to
secure the farming of the displaced people in the area, local
media said here today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted local military sources as saying that the
deployement is to be made after a decision was made at a joint
meeting of northern Uganda's Kitgum Disaster Committee, the army
and the district council.
</P>
<P>
About 60,000 people in Kitgum had been displaced people due to
the harassment of the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) in the north.
</P>
<P>
local displaced people asked the authorities to provide
maximum security for harvesting during the rainy season.
</P>
<P>
LRA had penetrated into the district in February this year to
kill 350 people and burnt down several houses.
</P>
<P>
The district decided to relocate the displaced by mid of the
next month and advised them to plant quick harvesting crops like
potatoes, sorghum and green vegetables.
</P>
<P>
lRA, with 700-800 members now from last year's 2,000, is a
rebel launching a ten-year guerrilla war to topple Ugandan
government led by President Yoweri Museveni. It has bases in
southern Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
