<HEADLINE> Grenade Thrown at Settlers' House in Ras Amud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 22 (Xinhua) -- A grenade was thrown Friday
night at the house occupied by Jewish settlers in East Jerusalem's
Ras Amud Arab neighborhood, but no one was hurt, Israel Radio
reported today.
</P>
<P>
No one has claimed responsibility for the attack, and Israeli
police have not made any arrests yet.
</P>
<P>
The attack came after the Wednesday night's shooting attack
against two Jewish religious students near the Damascus Gate in
the Muslim Quarter of the Old City. One of the students was killed
and the other seriously injured by automatic rifle fired by
unknown Muslim militant.
</P>
<P>
Israel reacted strongly to the attack by setting up a police
station near the site of shooting and increasing armed protection
of Jews walking through the Muslim Quarter. A number of
Palestinian residents suspected of involvement in the attack have
been arrested by Israeli police.
</P>
<P>
Ras Amud is a controversial neighborhood, where a group of
Jewish seminary students are residing in two houses allegedly
bought by American billionaire Irving Moskowitz who intends to
build a Jewish settlement in the area.
</P>
<P>
The students moved in late September under a deal to replace
the two Jewish settler families which occupied the houses and
sparked a widespread crisis between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem has been at the center of the Israeli-Palestinian
disputes: Israel maintains it has sovereign control over the
whole holy city including the mostly Arab East Jerusalem it has
been occupying since the 1967 War, while the Palestinians hope to
establish an independent state with East Jerusalem as its
capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
