<HEADLINE> Residents in Tanzanian Capital Drink Sub-Standard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 22 (Xinhua) -- About three million
residents in the Tanzanian capital of Dar es Salaam drink dirty water
that fail to meet the international standards, Daily News reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The city has no supply of safe, adequate and reliable water because
of lack of necessary infrastructure which has been caused by financial
difficulties, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Mtoni, Upper Ruvu and the Lower Ruvu water treatment plants
cannot treat water to the World Health Organization (WHO) standards,
said Rajab Mtoro from Dar es Salaam Water and Sewerage Authority
(DAWASA) at a workshop Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Mtoni plant is in a state of disrepair while its source of
water has inadequate flow, the official read a speech on behalf of the
DAWASA Director Arcado Mutalema at the workshop on The Dar es
Salaam Water Demand.
</P>
<P>
"The Lower Ruvu water filters have never worked and are currently
out of date," Mutualemwa revealed.
</P>
<P>
The buildings for the water treatment plants have cracks and
their equipment is old, Mutalema said.
</P>
<P>
The poor situation of water provision in the city is due to lack of
investment over the 30 years, he said, complaining that the water
tariffs has been kept low and the subsidy from the government is
inadequate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
