<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kim Appeals for National Support to Overcome Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam apologized Saturday to the people for the nation'
economic problems and pleaded for collective cooperation to
overcome the crisis.
</P>
<P>
In his nationwide-televised address, the President asked the
people to join forces with the government's efforts to overcome the
present economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive admitted that the dazzling development over
the past 30 years had also given birth to structural problems in
the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
Some strategic industries had been protected in their competition
with foreign counterparts and had received financial and tax benefits,
he said.
</P>
<P>
With the advent of the era of boundless competition following the
inauguration of the World Trade organization, South Korean companies
reached the maximum limit of their growth potential under the
high-cost and low-efficiency structure, going bankruptcy and leaving
financial institutions with bad debts, President Kim said.
</P>
<P>
Kim pledged every means possible to minimize the problems from
financial structural changes within the range of possible economic
sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
"We will make use of International Monetary Fund (IMF)'s support
loan to acquire urgent foreign currency, and we will make utmost
efforts to endure the burden for structuring," the President said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea filed on Friday evening the application for 20
billion US-dollar loan from the IMF as a last resort to save its
economy, paralyzed by corporate bankruptcies, devaluation of
national currency and crumbling stock market.
</P>
<P>
Promising the government's own budget reductions, Kim asked that
"the managers do more for industrial restructuring than competing for
loans, workers do more to improve productivity than to fight for
higher wages."
</P>
<P>
The President asked economic and social leaders to provide the role
model for frugality.
</P>
<P>
Under the basic economic conditions such as healthy financing and
consumer prices, competitive in industry and exports, South Korea can
overcome the crisis, if all politicians, businessmen and workers can
unite with a determination to do, Kim said.
</P>
<P>
The President also said he will seek support from South Korea's
allies and cooperate with the leaders in overcoming the nation's
economic difficulties at the forthcoming Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) meeting in Vancouver, Canada.
</P>
<P>
The President is leaving Saturday afternoon for Vancouver to attend
the November 24-25 APEC leaders' meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
