<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.African Health Facilities on Alert Against Cholera Outbreak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Health facilities in
South Africa have been put on alert to prevent a possible cholera
outbreak in the country, the Department of Health said Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
The move follows the death of 184 people in neighboring
Mozambique from the disease in recent months.
</P>
<P>
With the recent spread of the disease southward in Africa, the
possibility of an outbreak in South Africa does exist if
precautionary measures were not taken, the department said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Since international experience had shown that travel and trade
restrictions did not prevent the spread of the disease, emphasis
mut be placed on detection and prevention within the country, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
To prevent a possible outbreak, provincial health facilities
had been placed on alert and the necessary guidelines for
managing a potential cholera outbreak had been distributed,
according to the department.
</P>
<P>
"Bacteriological surveillance is being carried out in sewers
of the major cities to detect the cholera bacteria and laboratory
facilities are prepared for confirming clinical diagnosis of the
disease," said the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
