<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) experienced sharp falls this week.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Composite Index ended the week 117.38 points
lower at 560.09, the all Main Board shares Emas Index eased 35.58
points to 154.09, the Industrial Index dipped 207.53 points to
1,118.58 and the Second Board Index fell 65.92 points to 262.25.
</P>
<P>
The KLSE, which saw continuous plunge in share prices for the
first few trading days this week, technically rebounded on Friday,
the last trading day this week.
</P>
<P>
According to analysts, the rebound was expected to be extended
to next week, aiming for the 600 level before stabilizing on
continued strong buying support, and with the market having been
oversold over the past four days the apparent massive forced
selling was expected to ease.
</P>
<P>
A decline in the ringgit, rising interest rates, concerns over
corporate deals and year-end factors were said to have made
investors jittery.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit, which fell to a historical low of 3.5201 against
the U.S. dollar earlier this week, settled the week at 3.4750/50
to the greenback from 3.3150/25 at last week's close.
</P>
<P>
Fiamma Holdings Bhd, a company involved in the distribution,
assembly and manufacture of quality household appliances and home
finishing products, made its debut on the Main Board on the second
trading day this week and ended the week at 1.84 ringgit, below
its offer price of 2.35 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
During the week, total volume traded increased to 1.905 billion
shares valued at 5.664 billion ringgit (1.6322 billion U.S.
dollars) from 1.078 billion shares worth 4.687 billion ringgit
(1.3507 billion dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Main Board turnover rose to 1.704 billion shares valued at
4.790 billion ringgit (1.3804 billion dollars) from 760.462
million shares valued at 2.574 billion ringgit (741.7867 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals were at 239.909 million shares worth 2.206
billion ringgit (635.7348 million dollars) from 167.062 million
valued at 1.155 billion ringgit (332.853 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Turnover of the Second Board increased to 201.003 million
shares valued at 874.195 million ringgit (251.9293 million
dollars) from 152.311 million shares worth 957.966 million ringgit
(276.0708 million dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
