<HEADLINE> Team Formed to Monitor Radio Air Time Allocation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 22 (Xinhua) -- An inter-party committee has
been set up in Kenya to assist the Electoral Commission to
monitor the air time allocation by state radio and television to
all registered political parties in the run-up to the December 29
general elections.
</P>
<P>
This was agreed Friday at a meeting between representatives of
24 registered political parties, the Electoral Commission and the
state-run Kenya Broadcasting Corporation (KBC) which is one of
the major media in the country, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agreed that each of the 24 political parties would
appoint one person to the committee, and the KBC and the Electoral
Commission will also be represented.
</P>
<P>
The committee will ensure that equal, fair and balanced
coverage is accorded to all candidates and political parties,
allocate free air time on KBC Radio and Television for parties
and candidates to sell their programs.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, presidential candidate Raila Odinga
proposed that the KBC assign crews to the 15 declared
presidential candidates and that each party gets 10 minutes of
free air time on national radio and TV per week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
