<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Disappointing Year for NZ Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 22 (Xinhua) -- The past year for the first
New Zealand coalition government has proved to be disappointing
with the partners beset with troubles one after another and their
support plummeting.
</P>
<P>
The poor performance of the coalition also cost the political
career of Prime Minister Jim Bolger, who was replaced by Transport
Minister and Minister for State-Owned Enterprises Jenny Shipley as
leader of the National Party early this month. Shipley will become
New Zealand's first woman prime minister in history after Bolger
resigns in early December.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll conducted in early October indicated that the
approval rate for the government sank to an all-time low: only
less than 10 percent of those polled approved the government,
while over 90 percent showed their disapproval.
</P>
<P>
The government was fraught with pains one after another shortly
 after the coalition was formed by the National Party and the New
Zealand First party last December.
</P>
<P>
The government had to spend most of its time and energy to deal
with many trivial issues, like a financial scandal of a MP of New
Zealand First party, which is a coalition partner; a scuffle
between a National Party MP and New Zealand First leader Winston
Peters; and a judicial review of the findings of a tax evasion
inquiry lodged by Peters, who is the deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The biggest setback for the government came in September when
92 percent of the voters rejected a compulsory savings scheme
masterminded by Peters to replace the present universal
superannuation. The scheme even encountered opposition from many
government ministers, including Shipley.
</P>
<P>
These incidents hampered the government from carrying out
normal business and prompted a disappointed National Party
minister to resign from the government, challenging Bolger's
ability to lead the government and his own party in particular.
</P>
<P>
To reassert his leadership in the government and in his
National Party, Bolger in October again signaled privatization of
state assets, a program differentiating National Party from New
Zealand First.
</P>
<P>
Hoping to revive the confidence of his supporters, Bolger said
he believed it was "springtime again" in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
But the "springtime" did not come as privatization efforts met
stiff opposition from New Zealand First, which insisted some
assets classified as "strategic" could not be sold under the
coalition agreement.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, support of the business communities for the coalition
also slid. A recent survey of business people in Wellington, the
capital, showed that only 2 percent of those polled thought the
coalition was good for business, while 62 percent thought it bad.
</P>
<P>
Now, with Shipley at the helm, the National Party hopes that
their fortune could be turned around.
</P>
<P>
The first difficulty facing Shipley is to cope with Peters, who
does not expect to enjoy the kind of good relationship with Bolger
as with Shipley.
</P>
<P>
Shipley has promised that the direction of the coalition and
the main points of the coalition agreement will not change, except
the style of the government.
</P>
<P>
This can be explained in many ways. One is that the National
Party will play the leading role in the government. But whether
Peters will allow this to happen is still a matter of
wait-and-see.
</P>
<P>
After two weeks of withholding support for Shipley to ponder
the pros-and-cons in working with a Shipley-led National Party,
New Zealand First finally decided last week to stay in the
coalition. The uncertainty following the National leadership
change was temporarily tided over.
</P>
<P>
But no one is now sure whether the coalition will get through
its full term of three years. Given the personality of both
Shipley and Peters, divergence may arise from time to time in the
future, creating fresh uncertainties for the relations between the
two partners.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, voters favor an early election. The latest
opinion poll showed that two thirds of those surveyed wanted an
early election instead of waiting for another two years. It also
indicated a Labor Party victory if an election is held now.
</P>
<P>
The coalition must do better in the future. If the voters see
no significant change in government performance in the near
future, both partners are destined to be voted out of the
government two years later, if they can hang on that long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
