<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of
crude palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week all
higher.
</P>
<P>
On the CPO physicals market this week, December South ended the
week at 1,725 ringgit (497.1 U.S. dollars) per ton, five ringgit
higher from last week's close at 1,720 ringgit (495.7 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals are expected to hover around the current
levels due to currency factors next week with prices unlikely to
drop as the commodity is still enjoying good demand, a dealer
said.
</P>
<P>
Prices next week are projected to remain steady at above the
1,700 ringgit (490 dollars) level, reflecting the firmer trend on
the futures, the dealer said, adding that the projection by
private forecaster Van Wong that Malaysia's November palm oil
output was down 13.2 percent to 792,000 tons to some extent will
influence market sentiment and spark speculative activities.
</P>
<P>
This week, the price of tin on the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market
(KLTM) rose 13 sen to close the week at 19.33 ringgit (5.57
dollars) per kg compared to 18.01 ringgit (5.19 dollars) per kg
last week.
</P>
<P>
Turnover this week declined to 423 tons against 358 tons last
week with locals, Europeans and Japanese buyers accounting for
the bulk of the transactions.
</P>
<P>
The tin price next week is likely to remain firm, expected to
touch 19.50 ringgit level on follow-through buying support and
bullish sentiment from the London Metal Exchange (LME) based on
the KLTM's steadier performance this week which stemmed from
strong buying interest influenced by London's uptrend, according
to dealers.
</P>
<P>
Rubber prices on the Malaysian rubber market this week were
also higher in a quiet market on lack of interest from buyers, as
November RSS One ended 1.5 sen higher at 278.5 sen (80 U.S.
cents) per kg and SMR 20 was up 5.0 sen to 282.5 sen (81 U.S.
cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market indicator price for November 20 was at 201.54
Malaysia/Singapore cents (sen) per kg against 202.40 cents (sen)
on November 13.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average stood at 200.73 cents (sen) versus
204.86 cents (sen) last week.
</P>
<P>
As dealers predicted, the local rubber market is expected to be
firmer next week on technical adjustments due to currency factors,
however, trading is expected to be thin in the absence of fresh
leads.
</P>
<P>
Prices are expected to move up on shortage of raw materials
which was said to continue in the near-term due to the rainy
season which affected rubber production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
