<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Settlement Offered in Consideration of Affirmative Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- A settlement with the
offering of more than 300,000 U.S. dollars in back pay could end a
landmark U.S. Supreme Court case on diversity in hiring and firing
in order to protect affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Washington-based Black Leadership Forum, a civil
rights coalition, agreed to pay the huge amount of money,
two-thirds of the 433,500 dollars demanded by Sharon Taxman from
the Piscataway Board of Education, New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
Board attorney David Rubin is asking the Supreme Court to
declare the suit moot.
</P>
<P>
Taxman, a 50-year-old white woman, sued the board after she was
laid off from teaching in 1989 while a black teacher with equal
qualifications was retained in the name of diversity.
</P>
<P>
Taxman, who was hired in 1992, continued her pursuit of back
pay. She won a favorable ruling from a federal appeals court last
year.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Friday, "Once the case was accepted by the
court ... a number of national civil rights organizations
expressed to the board their genuine concern that an adverse
ruling in this case could gut the infrastructure of affirmative
action across the country."
</P>
<P>
Civil rights leaders feared that pursuing the case could have
done more harm than good to the affirmative action -- a formal
effort to increase employment and school admission opportunities
for the country's women and ethnic minorities to overcome past
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
The board voted 5-3 late Thursday to end its appeal, saying it
was in the best interest of the district.
</P>
<P>
The nation's Supreme Court had agreed to hear the case in
January.
</P>
<P>
In the review of the first affirmative action dispute this
term, the court let stand California's Proposition 209, a ban on
race and gender preference in hiring and school admission.
</P>
<P>
Jesse Jackson, who helped raise some of the money in the
settlement, said Friday the case was "riddled with problems; the
battle is fierce."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
