<HEADLINE> Indian President Keeps Close Watch on Fluid Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Indian President Kocheril
Raman Narayanan is reported to have been keeping a close watch on
the fluid political situation in the country in the wake of the
Congress party's threat to withdraw support to the coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
Political circles here are agog with speculation over the
president's reaction to the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Although the strategy adopted by both the Congress and the
United Front (UF) appears to be one of buying time, once the
Congress decides to deliver its letter informing the president of
its decision to withdraw support for the UF government, the scene
would automatically shift to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Narayanan may not be in a hurry to decide on
dissolution of the parliament if the government led by I.K. Gujral
falls.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, he may explore the possibility of another
government before deciding on general elections.
</P>
<P>
The president knows that none of the MPs wants to face mid-term
elections. Elections may be the last option for the president, a
political party leader said.
</P>
<P>
The Congress, the main supporter of the 14-party United Front
government, has demanded the government to sack Dravida Munnetra
Kazhagam (DMK), one of the constituents of the UF coalition, for
its links with the assassination of former Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi in 1991.
</P>
<P>
As the UF has already rejected the Congress demand to dump the
DMK, it is now up to the prime minister to either write to the
Congress president or talk to him personally to resolve the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
If the Congress delivers the letter of support withdrawal to
the president, he may refer it to the Lower House of Parliament.
Since the House is in session, the trial of strength has to be
decided on the floor of the House.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
