<HEADLINE> Croatia Hails UNTAES Scheduled Pullout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Croatian Foreign Ministry
issued a communique here today hailing the United Nations
Transitional Administration for Eastern Slavonia (UNTAES) for its
scheduled pullout of Croatia when its mission terminates on
January 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The communique was issued after the Administrator William
Walker confirmed at a news conference here today that the United
Nations police will stay in Eastern Slavonia as observers to help
establish peace and trust between the nations and protect local
residents after UNTAES withdraws in January.
</P>
<P>
The administrative power in Eastern Slavonia will be fully
transmitted to the Croatian government, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
The communique also said that UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan
sent a letter in reply to Croatian Foreign Minister Glonich
guaranteeing that UNTAES will pull out of Croatia on schedule.
</P>
<P>
The UN police, whose task will be to prevent transgressions and
provocations, will be allowed to stay in the country until the end
of October next year, the communique said,
</P>
<P>
it is beneficial for UN observers to remain in order to prevent
behaviors that might disrupt peace and the integration process.
</P>
<P>
Neven Jurica, the spokesman for the Croatian government, told
reporters that the smooth ending of the UNTAES's mission indicates
that peace and integration along the Danube River has been
established, and the Croatian government has maintained
territorial sovereignty as recognized by the international society.
</P>
<P>
Jurica also said that Croatia is ready to invite the United
Nations to send 150 observers to supervise the peace process in
the Danube area of Croatia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
