<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Senior Official on Central Bank's role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 22 (Xinhua) -- India's new governor of the
Reserve Bank of India (RBI) Bimal Jalan has said that the central
bank in a developing economy like India should concern itself with
employment generation and poverty eradication as much as inflation
control.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Business Standard today quoted the governor as
saying that "Inflation control is important but much depends on
what kind of trade-off you want. The central bank in a developing
country has to determine what level of inflation is acceptable for
achieving what level of growth."
</P>
<P>
The RBI's role is different from a central bank in a developed
economy, where the main concerns are price stability, employment
and exchange rate stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the lesson from the Southeast Asia crisis, Jalan said that
"the broad lessons for India are that you have to be constantly
watchful and take a medium-term view of the economy. We should not
take stability for granted. If you perceive a problem, it is
better to take action now rather than later."
</P>
<P>
Yet he refused to discuss the value of the Indian currency
rupee.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was better to wait for detailed studies on the
Southeast Asia crisis before taking a view.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
