<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspended Thai Finance Firms Urged to Increase Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's financial
restructuring authorities (FRA) Friday announced criteria for the
rehabilitation of 58 suspended finance firms, urging them to
increase capital for restoring operations.
</P>
<P>
Under the criteria, the 58 firms, whose operations were
suspended in June and August this year by the government due to
shortage of funds, are to maintain a capital-to-risk assets ratio
at 15 percent for the first year, 12 percent for the second year,
and 10 percent for the third year.
</P>
<P>
The firms are also required to work out plans to repay debts
and improve management, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
The FRA is expected to submit a report on the current position
of the 58 finance firms to the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
for review early next month to facilitate the transfer of the
IMF's second lot of loans from its 17.2 billion U.S. dollar aid
package.
</P>
<P>
Streamlining the financial sector was one of the requirements
set by the IMF when it decided to offer the aid package to
Thailand earlier this year. The suspended 58 firms currently
remain as the key problem facing the country's financial sector.
</P>
<P>
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus said last week during
his visit to Bangkok that he expected few, if any, of the
suspended firms will reopen.
</P>
<P>
The FRA is calling for mergers with the suspended firms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
