<HEADLINE> Hungarian Foreign Minister to US to Discuss NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Foreign Minister
Kovacs Laszlo will travel to the United States in February with
his Polish and Czech counterparts in an attempt to persuade
U.S. senators to agree to NATO's eastern expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
Laszlo said today that all European member countries of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization agreed to NATO's enlargement,
but in the U.S. Senate, at least 20 senators have raised
objections to the necessity of the expansion.
</P>
<P>
Laszlo is worried about the U.S. Senate's disapproval of NATO's
eastward expansion, so he will journey to Washington with the
Polish and Czech foreign ministers to meet with them, Laszlo said.
</P>
<P>
At a NATO summit in Madrid in July, Hungary, Poland and the
Czech Republic were accepted as new members in the first group to
join NATO by 1999.
</P>
<P>
The participation of NATO in 1999 and the European Union in
2002, the Hungarian minister said, will be a turning point in
Hungarian history. 
</P>
