<HEADLINE> Thailand, Vietnam to Start Joint Marine Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Vietnam will
start a joint survey of marine resources in the waters of the Gulf
of Thailand which once triggered disputes between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The survey is expected to be conducted from November 26 to
December 10 to cover an area of 33,150 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that Thailand and Vietnam will carry out
such a project to assess the marine resources in the Gulf of
Thailand, local newspapers said today.
</P>
<P>
The Thai-Vietnam Joint Commission on Fisheries and Law and
Order at Sea, which is chaired by vice foreign ministers of the
two countries, approved the project in April last year in a bid to
forge cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In August this year, the Vietnamese and Thai foreign ministries
signed in Bangkok an agreement to delimit some 6,500 square
kilometers of overlapping maritime claims between Thailand and
Vietnam in the Gulf of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the pact ended nearly two decades of disputes
between the two countries over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab Chaiyasarn, who signed the
agreement, said then that the pact marked a transition from
conflict to joint cooperation in the exploration of natural
resources and security at sea.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Manh Cam also said that the
agreement was a big leap forward in the diplomatic relations
between the two countries and reflected the two countries' will to
cooperate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
