<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Welcomes Breakthrough in Pre-Four-party Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korea welcomed the
breakthrough in diplomatic talks to realize the four-way talks on
peace on the Korean Peninsula, the Presidential Office said in a
statement released today.
</P>
<P>
An agreement was reached at the third round of preliminary
meetings held in New York Friday by the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK), South Korea, China and the United States
to hold the first session of the Four-party Talks on december 9,
in Geneva, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
"We assess it to be the result of a common understanding that
the job of setting peace on the Korean Peninsula by the parties
concerned is more pressing than anything else," Presidential
Spokesman Shin Woo-jae said.
</P>
<P>
The Four-way Talks is aimed at working out a peace mechanism on
the Korean Peninsula to replace an armistice treaty signed between
the so-called "United Nations" command led by the U.S. and the
DPRK-China side in 1953 to end the three year Korean War.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said, "we look forward to seeing all parties
concerned showing the same sincerity in the talks and work out
broad measures for easing tensions and building trust on the
Korean Peninsula and contributing to peace and stability in
Northeast Asia as well."
</P>
<P>
The Four-party Talks was jointly proposed by South Korean
President Kim Young-sam and U.S. President Bill Clinton in April
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary to Control Forint's Rate of Depreciation Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, November 21 (Xinhua) -- From January 1, 1998, the
depreciation rate of the forint, the Hungarian currency, will be
controlled within a 0.1 percentage rate, local newspapers reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The decision, made jointly by government and the National Bank
of Hungary, said the forint's automatic devaluation rate will fall
to 0.9 percent from the present 1 percent beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the decision was based on the country's
improved economy. The growth of GDP in the country this year will
outstrip the former figure of 4 percent, and the budget deficit
will be less than the former plan, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The country's rate of inflation this year will reportedly fall
to 18 percent from 23 percent last year, the export volume is much
more than the import volume, and the real revenue of residents
will increase by 4 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued to the press, a noted economist said that
although the forint depreciation rate is slightly lower, it shows
that the Hungarian economy has returned to the road of
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
