<HEADLINE> Museums on Move to Share Knowledge With People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Beijing residents are gaining
easier access to knowledge in the municipal government's drive to
popularize science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Displays stored in museums are moving out to be shared by more
people, said Li Yanjun, an official with the social development
department of Beijing Science and Technology Commission.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the capital's more than 30 scientific and
technological museums will be invited to created paintings and
illustrations to circulate in the city's roadside stands next
year, according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Ranging from 10 meters to 100 meters long, the stands will
cover a wide scope of knowledge, from ideas on environmental
protection to what medical treatments have been established.
</P>
<P>
The stands can be found along streets in each of the city's
districts and in 10 popular parks, including the Zizhu (Purple
Bamboo) Garden, Zhongshan Park and the Botanical Garden.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that, museums are also encouraged to arrange
tours for the displays, especially to villages, where science and
technology center are almost empty.
</P>
<P>
Beijing set up a special committee to popularize science and
technology in 1995. Since then, there has been an annual
government investment in science and technology popularization,
which started at 5 million yuan (602,000 US dollars) in 1995 and
is increasing by 20 percent each year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
