<HEADLINE> ASEAN Plans to Relax Foreign Equity Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asian businessmen
will push for the further liberalization of foreign equity
investments in the region next year to boost confidence and lure
back investors, the Philippine Daily Inquirer said today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Khoo Hock Aun, executive director of the ASEAN
Business Forum (ABF), as saying that allowing foreigners to own up
to 100 percent equity even in domestic-oriented enterprises is one
of the key measures being considered to boost foreign direct
investments in the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
Some ASEAN countries allowed full foreign ownership in
export-oriented enterprises in the early 1980s as a strategy to
attract foreign investors, Khoo said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the ABF feel that this strategy is applicable to
the current crisis but this time they want full foreign equity
extended even to domestic industries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"What the region needs now is stability and the best way to
achieve this is to attract more foreign direct investments in the
region especially next year," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ABF meeting in Kuala Lumpur next month will discuss the
further easing of foreign ownership, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since a currency crisis hit Southeast Asian countries in July,
foreign investors have lost their confidence in the region and
shifted their funds to other parts of the world. ASEAN members are
taking confidence-building measures to lure back investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
