<HEADLINE> El Nino Brings Severe Drought to Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 22 (Xinhua) -- The El Nino phenomenon is
affecting the Philippines and 36 provinces, nearly half of the
country, are suffering severe droughts.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Bulletin newspaper today quoted a Weather Bureau
report as saying that rainfall was less than 40 percent of the
normal rate over the past three months in Luzon, Mindoro,
Marinduque, Romblon, Panay, Negros, Samar and parts of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
It said that other provinces have experienced "critical
rainfall deficiency," or less than 40 percent below normal for one
to two months.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that drier-than-normal weather conditions could
cause moderate to severe droughts in the country in the next five
months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, authorities said that the water level at the Angat
Dam in Bulacan province has dipped to "a very critical" 20 meters
below the rule curve.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine capital of Manila may have to resort to water
rationing before the middle of 1998 if Angat Dam is not
replenished, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Metropolitan Waterworks and Sewerage System, a water supply
company in the capital, also warned Friday that if the situation
worsens, water supply in Manila will be limited to two to three
hours a day and at the worst, taps will only flow every other day.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
