<HEADLINE> Nature Reserves in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, November 22 (Xinhua) -- The Bouyei-Miao Autonomous
Prefecture of southwest China's Guizhou Province recently set up
four nature reserves to protect endangered plants.
</P>
<P>
The four reserves -- the 5,000-hectare Longtoudashan Nature
Reserve for Bryophytes, the 2,000-hectare Xianghepeng Nature
Reserve for Broadleaf Trees, the 3,000-hectare Pogang Nature
Reserve for Karst Plants, and the 2,000-hectare Qingshuihe Scenic
Forest Nature Reserve -- were set up in the prefecture because it
is situated on the upper valley in a karst region. The
establishement of these nature reserves will be conducive to
preventing soil erosion, according to Li Yuecheng, deputy
commissioner of the prefecture.
</P>
<P>
He said that the preserves will also help protect the ecology
and preserve natural resources.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, the prefecture has drafted some regulations
for the four reserves.  
</P>
