<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Province Gets Rid of Tropical Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese public health
officials has recently announced that Hunan, in south central
China, which used to have a high incidence of filariasis, has
finally rid itself of the disease.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Health Organization, filariasis ranks
with malaria as one of the six tropical diseases most harmful to
humans.
</P>
<P>
About 30 million Chinese in 15 provinces suffer from the
disease and Hunan alone had some 1.6 million cases.
</P>
<P>
The province launched an all-out attack on the disease in 1952,
sending medicines to remote mountainous areas. By 1986, the
Ministry of Health declared that filariasis had basically been
reduced in Hunan.
</P>
<P>
For the last decade, the province has continued its prevention
and treatment of the disease by building a monitoring
network. And, after a one-week check, experts say they are
convinced that filariasis has finally been eradicated in the
province.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth of fifteen provinces to get completely free
of the disease, health officials say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico to Help Communities Affected by El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican government
announced today a program to help communities affected by the El
Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Emilio Chuayffet said the northern states of
Baja California, Baja California Sur, Sonora, Chihuahua, Nayarit,
and Sinaloa may be the most affected by the natural phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Chuayffet said that about 500,000 people live in the six states.
</P>
<P>
The plan will help reduce the potential for further damage by
identifying maps of affected areas and high risk areas,
identification of river beds, drainage of urban basins, human
settlements that could be affected, and establishing emergency
plans to evacuate people.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his ministry will also coordinate with the
Integral Development of the Family and the Defense Ministry to
provide medical supplies, food and lodging.
</P>
<P>
He said that Mexicans will work together to reduce damage and
help those affected return to their normal activities as soon as
possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
