<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shell Mounds Reveal Prehistoric Life in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 22 (Xinhua) -- A recent study of shell mounds
along the Jiaodong Peninsula coast in east China's Shandong
Province has shown that people were living by farming there some
4,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The ancestors of people there built mound dwellings out of
shells some 10,000 years ago and depended on shellfish, fishing,
and hunting, according to a team of archaeologists from
Beijing-based Chinese Social Science Academy.
</P>
<P>
The team studied 23 mound sites scattered in 16 counties in
Shandong over the past two years and found that the shells were
smaller and fewer in number as time went by, suggesting a decline
in the shell resources because of the existence of shell-gathering
over a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
The decline in the number of shells is accompanied by an
increase in the amount of rice remains, indicating that the locals
shifted from fishing to farming, the scholars say.
</P>
<P>
The mound studies are just one example of how Chinese
archaeologists have begun to pay more attention to how ancient
people tried to adapt to the environment, something that has lead
to a new branch of the field -- environmental archaeology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
