<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Old Industrial Base Placing Hope on Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, November 22 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province in
northeast China plans to establish an export-oriented economy in
the next five years, sources at a provincial conference have
reported.
</P>
<P>
Wen Shizhen, Liaoning's governor, told the recent conference
that the province will get two-thirds of its 926 state-owned
enterprises to set up co-operative ventures with overseas
companies over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is the home to about a tenth of China's large- and
medium-sized state-owned enterprises and it gets more than 80
percent of its revenues from them, whose fixed assets are valued
at 500 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The attempt to prod the provincial economy will involve
bringing in foreign capital, technology, and managerial techniques
to the old enterprises, Wen said.
</P>
<P>
To further promote foreign trade, Liaoning will expand its
export volume to 23 billion U.S. dollars worth by the year 2002,
from last year's 13 billion dollars worth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
