<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Confident of Bright Future for Southeast Asia's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, Canada, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The current
financial difficulties in Southeast Asian nations can surely be
overcome after necessary economic structural readjustment, Chinese
Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the 9th ministerial meeting
of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC), Qian said that he
was quite confident that the economy in this region will have a
bright future.
</P>
<P>
Despite the financial crisis in some countries in the region,
the Asian Pacific rim is still a region with the fastest-growing
economy, Qian told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that the countries which sufferred from the
crisis will be able to overcome the difficulties and lay solid
foundation for a new round of economic growth, making even greater
contribution to regional and global economic development.
</P>
<P>
"We have full confidence in the prospects for the growth of the
East Asia economies," said Qian.
</P>
<P>
He listed three points of lessons from the financial
fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
"Faced with the growing trend towards globalization and
integration, all members need to constantly improve their
respective macro-economic management system and make timely
readjustments to the economic structure to be more responsive and
more flexible," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is an important prerequisite for an economy to adapt to
external changes and ensure its sound development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Financial turmoil in the Southeast Asia has cast shadows over
the ministerial meeting, which focused on liberalizing investment
and trade.
</P>
<P>
"Speculation has become a very salient problem in international
financial activities," Qian added, urging steps to be taken to
rein in excessive speculation.
</P>
<P>
"The increasingly closer economic ties have made it all the
more necessary for enhancing international and regional
cooperation, which will help maintain a stable and favorable
international economic environment for their economic growth and
development," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Such a cooperation is particularly important for developing
economies that are more vulnerable to external economic
fluctuations and speculations owing to their relatively weak
economic foundations," added the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
China has actively joined in the program of financial
assistance to Thailand and Indonesia. "We take a positive
attitude towards enhanced regional financial cooperation in Asia,"
Qian said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
