<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Compagnoni Wins World Cup Giant Slalom in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Italy's Deborah Compagnoni
achieved another women's World Cup Alpine giant slalom victory
Friday when she finished the run with a combined time of 2:52.60
at Park City, Utah of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Compagnoni, the reigning women's World Cup, world and Olympic
giant slalom champion, was fastest by nearly a full second in the
first run with a time of 1:26.69. She returned to the course on
C.B.'s Run and produced a sizzling second run 1:25.91 for an
unofficial winning combined time of 2:52.60.
</P>
<P>
Alexandra Meissnitzer of Austria used a spectacular second run
1:26.92 to jump from 13th to take second place on the podium with
a combined time of 2:56.01.
</P>
<P>
Third place went to Norway's Andrine Flemmen, who finished
2:56.46.
</P>
<P>
It was Compagnoni's sixth consecutive World Cup giant slalom
win (and world championship). Her winning margin of 3.41 seconds
registered the third largest in the history of women's World Cup
skiing. The record of 5.20 seconds was set in 1979 by
Switzerland's Marie Therese Nadig in a giant slalom in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Compagnoni takes over the overall points lead from German
Martina Ertl, who slipped to sixth place in Friday's giant slalom
after nearly falling twice and taking out a gate on her second
run.
</P>
<P>
Ertl finished second in the first run with a time of 1:27.67
and completed the race with a final time of 2:57.17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
