<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, November 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- China, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea,
the Republic of Korea and the United States agreed Friday to start
the Four-Party Talks on Korean Peninsula in Geneva, Switzerland,
on December 9.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached in the third preparatory meeting held
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
A joint press statement issued at the end of the meeting said
delegations to the preparatory meetings which had been held in New
York from August 5 to November 21, recognized the importance of
tension reduction and establishment of a durable peace on the
Peninsula and have reached the agreement.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said on Friday that
the United States would keep vigilance despite Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein agreed to the return of U.N. weapons inspectors
including four Americans.
</P>
<P>
"We must be constantly vigilant and resolute, and with our
friends and partners we must be especially determined to prevent
Saddam's ability to reconstitute his weapons of mass destruction
program," Clinton said at a ceremony at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the return of the inspectors to Baghdad was an
important achievement and the United States would do whatever to
make sure their mission be resumed unimpeded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
