<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anchorage to Host 2001 Special Olympics Winter Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Special Olympics
International (SOI) announced here today that the 2001 Special
Olympics World Winter Games will be held at Anchorage, Alaska.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Timothy Shriver, President of SOI,
and Kathinka Tunney, Chairman of the Special Olympics World Winter
Games committee.
</P>
<P>
Special Olympics is an international, year-round program of
sports training and competition for individuals with mental
retardation. One million athletes in 146 countries and regions
train and compete in 24 Olympic-type summer and winter sports,
making Special Olympics the world's largest private philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
The 2001 winter games are expected to attract some 2,000
athletes from 85 countries and regions over a seven-day period in
March. Specific dates have yet to be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the competitors, thousands of athlete family
members, volunteers and journalists are expected to attend the
games as well as spectators from all over the United States and
from the participating nations.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Special Olympics completed its sixth World
Winter Games in Toronto and Collingwood, Ontario. Nearly 1,900
athletes from 75 countries and regions competed during the
week-long event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
