<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crew Ordered to Abandon Satellite Temporarily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National
Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) today ordered the crew
aboard shuttle Columbia to temporarily abandon a tumbling
solar-watching satellite.
</P>
<P>
The Spartan satellite was released from the shuttle at 4:03
p.m. EST (2103 GMT) today, but failed to perform a pre-programmed
spin that would have indicated it was ready to begin its
free-flight.
</P>
<P>
Astronaut Kalpana Chawla attempted to retrieve the craft, but a
latching mechanism on the shuttle's robot arm failed to snare it.
As Chawla drove the crane back for another try, it inadvertently
bumped the 1 1/2-ton spacecraft, causing it to tumble.
</P>
<P>
The crew waited for the satellite to move into a safe position
for recapture, but after an hour they were told to steer the
shuttle away to leave enough propellant for a later rendezvous and
possible spacewalk to retrieve the craft.
</P>
<P>
Within an hour, NASA had lost any chance of conducting solar
observations with the satellite, now or later in the mission. The
space agency still wanted the satellite back, however, for the
trip home.
</P>
<P>
Spartan was supposed to observe for two days the sun's ionized
outer atmosphere, known as the corona, and the solar wind, the
charged particles hurtling from the sun. The solar wind can
disrupt radio communications and power stations on Earth.
</P>
<P>
Columbia's international crew of six was supposed to retrieve
Spartan Sunday night and then gear up for the practice spacewalk
Monday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Central Bankers Reassert Strict Euro Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FRANKFURT, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of European central
banks today reasserted the demand for strict adherence to the
qualification criteria of the planned single European currency,
the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a congress of European banks in Frankfurt today,
German central bank president Hans Tietmeyer said, "Any watering
down of the Euro requirements must be avoided."
</P>
<P>
This was the most important prerequisite to ensure a smooth
transition to the monetary union, he added.
</P>
<P>
Like Tietmeyer, French central bank governor Jean-Claude
Trichet also described the adherence to the Euro standards as "an
absolute condition for a smooth transition from national monetary
policies to a common monetary policy."
</P>
<P>
Expressing confidence in the punctual start of the Euro on
January 1, 1999, he also said, "The Euro must and will have the
credibility of the most credible European Exchange Rate Mechanism
currencies, in particular the guilder, the mark and the French
franc."
</P>
<P>
In order to qualify for the Euro, European Union states must
bring their budget deficit and national debt to no more than 3
percent and 60 percent of the gross domestic product respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
