<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Device to Measure Arteries' Elasticity Invented in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Greek doctors have invented an
angioscope which can be used to measure accurately the elasticity
of arteries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an international symposium on coronary disease
which began here today, Dr. Ch. Stefanadis, associate professor of
cardiology, said that the device, in the form of a catheter, opens
like a fork and sticks to the sides of the aorta. At the same
time, a second catheter measures the pressure and diameter of the
aorta.
</P>
<P>
He said that the technique contributed to the finding that
hormonal replacement therapy in post-menopausal women led to a
reduced risk of coronary disease, which was responsible for almost
50 percent of deaths in the Western countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
