<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four-Party Talks on Korean Peninsula to Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 21 (Xinhua) -- China, the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea, the Republic of Korea and the United
States agreed today to start the Four-Party Talks on Korean
Peninsula in Geneva, Switzerland, on December 9.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached in the third preparatory meeting held
here today.
</P>
<P>
A joint press statement issued at the end of the meeting said
delegations to the preparatory meetings which had been held in New
York from August 5 to November 21, recognized the importance of
tension reduction and establishment of a durable peace on the
Peninsula and have reached the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The agenda of the Four-Party Talks will be the establishment of
a peace regime on the Peninsula and issues concerning tension
reduction there, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Details about the delegations to the Four-Party Talks will be
announced prior to the opening of the plenary session, the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
The agreement shows that the parties concerned have reached
understanding on a wide range of issues and have common interests
in the maintaining of peace and stability of the Peninsula and in
the establishment of peace regime through Four-Party Talks, said
Chen Jian, Chinese delegation head and Assistant Foreign Minister.
</P>
<P>
He hopes that the concerned parties will make efforts to push
the formal talks to make progress in the spirit of equal
participation, patient consultation, seeking common ground while
reserving differences and advancing orderly and step by step.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side will maintain cooperation with other parties
concerned and will play a constructive role in the early
establishment of the peace regime in the Peninsula, Chen added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
