<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four-Party Talks on Korean Peninsula to Be Held in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, Canada, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S., China, the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea and South Korea agreed to
hold "primary talks" in Geneva next month on the Korean Peninsula,
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations will begin in Geneva on December 9 after a
long time of diplomatic consultations, said Albright, who is here
in Vancouver for an Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the meeting, which began today, she called the
upcoming four-party meeting a "significant diplomatic
accomplishment."
</P>
<P>
It will be the first international talks on the armistice in
place on the Korean Peninsula since 1953, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the talks are aimed at seeking a lasting peace and
stability on the Korean Peninsula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
