<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Keeps on Rising Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Johnes industrial
average kept on its rising track Friday and rose 54.46 points to
7,881.07, bringing the week's gain to 308.59, or about 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 592.04 million
shares, down slightly from Friday's tally of 601.80 million.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 4.12 to 963.10, and
the NYSE composite index rose 2.30 to 502.84, but the Nasdaq
composite index fell by 5.81 to 1,620.75.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell by 0.65 to 435.05.
But the American Stock Exchange composite index, which is dominated
by smaller companies, rose by 0.29 to 673.14.
</P>
<P>
The market rose eventually despite falling into negative
territory following reports that Yamaichi Securities of Japan,
crippled with debts of about 24 billion U.S. dollars, is going out
of business.
</P>
<P>
Stocks started the day higher, with the Dow gaining nearly 55
points, after Asian financial markets posted some big gains. Stocks
in Hong Kong surged by 5 percent overnight and Tokyo share prices rose
by 2.5 percent. Gains were also seen throughout Europe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
