<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hague Sacks Pro-European Conservative MP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Conservative Party leader
William Hague said today the resignation of pro-European MP Peter
Temple-Morris as a Conservative MP was "inevitable."
</P>
<P>
Hague, who expelled him from the Parliamentary Party, said, "He
is like a footballer who says he will play for the other side at
half-time."
</P>
<P>
"He had to go. We can't have MPs in the party who are not
committed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tory party officials said the reason why Hague decided to expel
the veteran Tory member was because Temple-Morris had "repeatedly
and publicly questioned his continued commitment to the
Conservative Party."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 59-year-old Temple-Morris also announced today that
he was resigning from the Conservative after being suspended from
the parliamentary party.
</P>
<P>
He said he would sit in the parliament as an Independent One
Nation Conservative, but he denied it was the beginning of a split
in the Conservative.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Temple-Morris, an MP for 24 years, had held two
meetings with Prime Minister Tony Blair about defecting, but
pulled back in October after another MP pressed Hague to soften
his line on the single currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
