<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's CSU Party Calls for Strict Adherence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Munich, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Germany's conservative
Christian Social Union (CSU) party today renewed its call for
strict adherence to the qualification criteria of the planned
single European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
In a position paper adopted today during a party congress in
Munich, the CSU said that under normal circumstances, future
members of the single currency should keep budget deficits well
below the limit of three percent of gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The three-percent limit should be viewed as "a maximum value"
which could only be touched during recession periods, the CSU
said.
</P>
<P>
The Bavarian sister party of German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
Christian Democratic Union (CDU) today also stressed that an
independent European central bank was "a central prerequisite" for
a stable Euro.
</P>
<P>
In an opening speech to the CSU party congress, Edmund Stoiber,
leader of the German state of Bavaria, also accused Kohl's party
of not being able to take a tough line on asserting the Euro
standards.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating his demand that the Euro criteria not be watered
down just in order to jump start the single currency at its
scheduled launching date of January 1, 1999, Stoiber said: "It is
the criteria that should determine the timetable." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
