<DOCNO> XIE19971122.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Finalizes Positions Towards New NATO Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Greece today finalized its
positions towards the new structure of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a joint meeting chaired by Foreign
Minister Theodoros Pangalos and and National Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos, Pangalos failed to give the details of Greece's
positions, but described Athens' positions as "solid and
constructive."
</P>
<P>
Greece's positions would help not only strengthen the country's
role in that context but also develop the alliance in the new
conditions that had been created in Europe and worldwide, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos also said that following the finalization of
Greece's positions, the desired results would be achieved at the
alliance defense ministers' meeting which will take place in
Brussels on December 1-3.
</P>
<P>
Greece has initially taken a positive view on the new structure
of the alliance, which provides for the establishment of
headquarters of its southeastern Europe flank in Italy with four
sub-headquarters in Greece, Italy, Spain and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Greece has said the abolition of the operational control areas
would not pose any problem for the country's sovereign rights and
Greece maintained the right of veto on issues regarding the
planning, design and materialization of military exercises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
