<HEADLINE> IMF Chief Welcomes South Korea's Request for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Michel Camdessus, the
Managing Director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) today
welcomed South Korea's request for financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
He said,"I have already assured the Korean authorities of our
full support," and "The management of the IMF has been in contact
with the Korean authorities in recent weeks on ways to overcome
the financial crisis, which has arisen despite sound macroeconomic
trends."
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief noted that an IMF mission would be dispatched to
Seoul next week to begin discussions with the Korean authorities.
"We will work closely and intensively with the authorities in
their finalization of a strong program which I could forward to
the Executive Board for approval under the IMF's emergency
financing mechanism."
</P>
<P>
Camdessus issued the statement in the wake of South Korea's
request for IMF's 20 billion U.S. dollar bailout of its foundering
economy.
</P>
<P>
South Korea also asked for an open line of credit in case 20
billion dollars was not enough. Some financial analysts say it
could take three times that amount to stabilize Seoul's economy.
</P>
<P>
Just last week, the South Korean government called the idea of
an IMF loan "unthinkable."
</P>
<P>
The economic situation has been worsening for almost a month,
due to a series of major corporate bankruptcies that brought a
loss of foreign confidence.
</P>
<P>
The crisis has been exacerbated by economic meltdowns elsewhere
in Asia, particularly in Thailand and Indonesia, both of which are
being rescued by the IMF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
