<HEADLINE> Astronauts Release Solar Observatory But Troubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Astronauts aboard the space
shuttle Columbia today released a sun-watching satellite, but
troubles occurred minutes later and the crew was ordered to
retrieve it immediately.
</P>
<P>
Astronaut Kalpana Chawla tried to grab the satellite with the
shuttle robot arm as the spacecraft soared over the Pacific, but
the satellite started to rotate, and she had to pull back the
crane, National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA)
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Spartan satellite was released shortly after 4:00 p.m.
without any problem. But it failed to perform a pirouette maneuver
to check its onboard systems and then began to spin slowly in
space.
</P>
<P>
Spartan was supposed to fly in the outer space for two days to
observe the sun's ionized outer atmosphere, known as the corona,
and the solar wind, the charged particles hurtling from the sun.
The solar wind can disrupt radio communications and power stations
on Earth.
</P>
<P>
Columbia's international crew of six was supposed to retrieve
Spartan Sunday night and then gear up for a practice spacewalk
Monday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
