<HEADLINE> Computers, Aerospace Predicted to Lead Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Strong demand for computers
and other high-tech goods should maintain the U.S. economy growing
into the next decade, a government report predicted today.
</P>
<P>
Apart from computers, hot industries for 1998 also should
include aerospace, dental equipment and management consulting, the
Commerce Department said today in a revival of an annual
publication discontinued since 1994.
</P>
<P>
However, businesses projected to shrink by the department's
"U.S. Industry &AMP; Trade Outlook '98" include shipbuilding, printing
services, footwear and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
The report evaluated 350 business sectors of manufacturing and
services. All major services and more than 80 percent of
manufacturing industries were projected to grow through next year
and beyond.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the department projected an inflation-adjusted growth
rate in manufacturers' shipments of 5.5 percent annually this year
and next.
</P>
<P>
Computer equipment is leading the way, with 29.6 percent growth
projected annually in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The importance of this industry to the economy cannot be
overstated," said Jonathan C. Menes, director of the department's
Office of Trade and Economic Analysis.
</P>
<P>
"If computers are excluded, the total of all manufacturing
output... would be about 3 percent annually for 1997 and 1998
instead of the 5.5 percent growth," he added.
</P>
<P>
With strong orders for commercial airliners, the aerospace
industry is projected to increase shipments by 17.4 percent a year
in 1997 and 1998. Dental equipment should increase 10.5 percent, a
result of the aging of the Baby Boom generation, and radio and
television equipment, 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
But more traditional sectors of the economy are expected to
show only modest growth compared with high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
Motor vehicles and parts shipments should increase 1.8 percent
in 1997 and 1998. The slower growth of the driving-age population
is cutting into sales, but the average cost per vehicle is rising
as older drivers opt for luxury vehicles, especially larger sport
utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, housing starts are slowing so growth in consumer
durable goods should average only 1.3 percent in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Some industries face not just slow growth, but contraction.
Shipbuilding should fall 8.5 percent this year and next, a victim
of reduced defense spending. Some printing services such as
typesetting, platemaking and production of color separations
should decrease 6.5 percent as computerization transforms the
industry.
</P>
<P>
Other declines are expected in industries suffering from
competition from imports: handbags and purses, down 6.1 percent;
footwear, down 2.1 percent; and jewelry, down 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Among services, a range of computer-related services such as
data processing all are projected to show better than 10 percent
growth in receipts, as are professional services such as
management consulting, public relations and accounting.
</P>
<P>
Travel spending should have a healthy gain of 7.9 percent, a
reflection that many households have purchased the big-ticket
goods they want during the nearly seven years of economic
expansion and are spending disposable income on vacations.
</P>
<P>
Growth in health care services is projected to rise 5.6 percent
this year and 5.9 percent in 1998. Still, U.S. health spending,
forecast at 1.16 trillion U.S. dollars next year, remains 13.5
percent of total economic output, the highest of any
industrialized nation.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department issued annual industrial outlook
reports from 1959 through 1994, but had to suspend the annual
publication due to government budget cuts. The renewal of its
publication is a product of a joint venture between the department
and the McGraw-Hill Companies this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
