<HEADLINE> Clinton Vows to be Vigilant against Iraq Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Friday that the United States would keep vigilance despite
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein agreed to the return of U.N.
weapons inspectors including four Americans.
</P>
<P>
"We must be constantly vigilant and resolute, and with our
friends and partners we must be especially determined to prevent
Saddam's ability to reconstitute his weapons of mass destruction
program," Clinton said at a ceremony at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the return of the inspectors to Baghdad was an
important achievement and the United States would do whatever to
make sure their mission be resumed unimpeded.
</P>
<P>
"We must make sure that inspectors are able to resume their
mission unimpeded," he said. "They must be able to proceed with
their work without interference to find, to destroy, to prevent
Iraq from building nuclear, chemical and biological weapons and
the missiles to carry them."
</P>
<P>
The White House said Washington was looking at how the
inspection teams could assume a "stronger presence" in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The United States believes they are going to have a stronger
presence in Iraq in order to accomplish" their work, White House
spokesman Mike McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
McCurry declined to specify what kind of stronger presence
would be taken, and only said, "There are a variety of ways you
can make it stronger." Political analysts speculated that that
could include more flights of U-2s over Iraq for U.S. mission or
an enlarged inspection team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
